{"title_page": "Gary Lee (journalist)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Gary Lee\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_date                = <!-- {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place               = \n| death_date                = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place               = \n| education                 = [[Phillips Academy]]\n| alma_mater                = [[Amherst College]]\n| occupation                = [[journalist]],<br/>[[travel writer]]\n| years_active              = 33\n| employer                  = ''[[Washington Post]]'',<br/>''[[Time Magazine]]''\n| known_for                 = \n| notable_works             = \n| home_town                 = [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n| partner                   = \n| children                  = \n| parents                   = \n| awards                    = Lowell Thomas,<ref name=twsFebL18/>\n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| footnotes                 = \n| box_width                 = \n}}\n\n'''Gary Lee''' is an American [[journalist]] with a focus on foreign policy, [[travel writer|travel writing]] and environmental issues. He wrote for the ''[[Washington Post]]'' as well as ''[[Time Magazine]]''. He speaks five languages including [[Russian language|Russian]]<ref name=twsFebL17/> German, French and Spanish, and he was the Washington Post's Moscow Bureau Chief.<ref name=twsFebL17/><ref name=twsFebL21>{{cite news\n |author= Ken Ringle\n |title= The New Yorker's Literary Lion Cub \n |newspaper= Washington Post  \n |date= August 6, 1998\n |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/daily/remnick.htm\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref> He was twice nominated for the Pulitzer Prize for foreign coverage and won the [[Lowell Thomas Award]] for travel journalism for his coverage of [[9/11]].<ref name=twsFebL18>{{cite news\n |title= Notable Alumni in the field of Journalism\n |publisher= Phillips Academy\n |date= 2011-02-12\n |url= http://www.andover.edu/About/Newsroom/TheMagazine/Fall09/Pages/OldBlue.aspx\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120309015334/http://www.andover.edu/About/Newsroom/TheMagazine/Fall09/Pages/OldBlue.aspx\n |archive-date= 2012-03-09\n |url-status= dead\n }}</ref><ref name=twsFebL17>{{cite news\n |title= Where In the World\n |publisher= Edge Travel Magazine\n |date= 2011-02-12\n |url= http://www.edgemagonline.com/travel1.htm\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref> He was elected to the position of charter trustee at [[Phillips Academy]] in 2009. In 2007, he left the ''Washington Post'' to become a freelance journalist.<ref name=twsFebL11>{{cite news\n |author= Gary Lee\n |title= Ten Favorite Hotels\n |newspaper= Washington Post\n |date= November 2, 2007\n |url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/travellog/2007/11/ten_favorite_hotels.html\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nLee grew up in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], the fourth child in a family of eleven. He attended [[Phillips Academy]] in [[Andover, Massachusetts]] between 1970 and '74. His studies there centered on English literature and modern languages. He began his reporting career at Andover as a writer for ''The Phillipian'', the campus newspaper, and general manager of WPAA, the school's radio station. Lee, in a later interview with [[travel writer]] Ross Potts, thought that his parents realized that he had a [[wanderlust]] and urge to explore the world.<ref name=twsFebL15>{{cite web\n |title       = Gary Lee 1974\n |publisher   = Phillips Academy\n |date        = 2011-02-12\n |url         = http://www.andover.edu/Giving/Profiles/Pages/GaryLee.aspx\n |access-date  = 2011-02-12\n |url-status     = dead\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100604050712/https://www.andover.edu/Giving/Profiles/Pages/GaryLee.aspx\n |archive-date = 2010-06-04\n |df          = \n}}</ref> Lee graduated from Andover in 1974, the school's first co-educational class; among his classmates were many future writers, including [[poetry|poets]] [[Chris Agee]] and [[Karl Kirchwey]], writer [[Nate Lee]], publisher and activist [[Ted Nace]], editor [[Sara Nelson (editor)|Sara Nelson]], and political analyst and writer [[Heather Mac Donald]]. Lee completed his secondary school education in studies at Uppingham School, a private academy in Rutland County, England. Lee attended [[Amherst College]] and graduated ''cum laude'' in 1979, with a double major in Russian language and Development Studies with particular interest in Africa. He was editor in chief of the Amherst Student, the campus newspaper, an avid track runner, and dj of a jazz radio program.\n\n==Career==\nIn his early career, Lee worked at ''[[Time Magazine]]'' first as a writer focusing on the [[Natural environment|environment]] and later as a correspondent in the magazine's bureau in Germany. In 1984, he was hired by the ''Washington Post'' and became the paper's bureau chief in [[Moscow, Russia|Moscow]] from 1985-1989. There he led the coverage of the era of then Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev and the collapse of the Soviet Union. In a later interview, he described the experience as both \"brutal and exhilarating\" since it forced him to \"bang out long pieces on deadline almost daily\". Lee also covered Congress and served as the Post's National Environmental writer. Later, he became a travel writer for the Post specializing in eco tourism, and cultural travel issues. According to Lee's own accounting, he has written about more than 80 countries, stayed in over a thousand [[hotel]]s, [[motel]]s, and [[bed and breakfast]]s on assignments.<ref name=twsFebL11/> He has camped out near the [[Potomac River]] as well as taken the [[Trans-Siberian railway]] in Russia. In his reporting, Lee advised travelers on such matters as getting around Moscow,<ref name=twsFebL12a>{{cite news\n |author= Gary Lee\n |title= Moscow Calling: Tips for the Trip\n |newspaper= Washington Post\n |date= October 26, 2007\n |url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/travellog/2007/10/moscow_tips.html\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref> ecologically correct hotels,<ref name=twsFebL12b>{{cite news\n |author= Gary Lee\n |title= In D.C., It's Easy Going Green\n |newspaper= Washington Post\n |date= October 25, 2007\n |url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/travellog/2007/10/in_dc_its_easy_going_green.html\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref> safety on cruise ships,<ref name=twsFebL12c>{{cite news\n |author= Gary Lee\n |title= Are Cruise Ships Safe?\n |newspaper= Washington Post\n |date= October 4, 2007\n |url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/travellog/2007/10/are_cruise_ships_safe.html\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref> travel to Canada,<ref name=twsFebL12d>{{cite news\n |author= Gary Lee\n |title= Is Canada the Boring Girl Next Door?\n |newspaper= Washington Post\n |date= September 13, 2007\n |url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/travellog/2007/09/is_canada_the_boring_girl_next_1.html\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref> dining options,<ref name=twsFebL13a>{{cite news\n |author= Gary Lee\n |title= Put That French Fry Down!\n |newspaper= Washington Post\n |date= August 10, 2007\n |url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/travellog/2007/08/alternatives_to_french_fries_c.html\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref><ref name=twsFebL13b>{{cite news\n |author= Gary Lee\n |title= Domino's Pizza and Other Healthy Dining Options\n |newspaper= Washington Post\n |date= August 27, 2007\n |url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/travellog/2007/08/dominos_pizza_and_other_health_1.html\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref> avoiding [[hurricane]]s in the [[Caribbean Sea|Caribbean]],<ref name=twsFebL13c>{{cite news\n |author= Gary Lee\n |title= Hurricane Season: Too Risky for Caribbean Travel?\n |newspaper= Washington Post\n |date= July 19, 2007\n |url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/travellog/2007/07/hurricane_season_too_risky_for.html\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref> tipping customs,<ref name=twsFebL13d>{{cite news\n |author= Gary Lee\n |title= $32 Tip Included\n |newspaper= Washington Post\n |date= May 17, 2007\n |url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/travellog/2007/05/32_tip_included.html\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref> private tour guides,<ref name=twsFebL13e>{{cite news\n |author= Gary Lee\n |title= Private Tour Guides: Worth It?\n |newspaper= Washington Post\n |date= March 5, 2007\n |url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/travellog/2007/03/private_tour_guides_worth_it.html\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref> and many other travel-related matters. \nSince 2007, Lee has written articles on sociological travel trends and environmental issues for several national magazines.\n\nLee was interviewed by travel writer [[Rolf Potts]] who assembled a collection of \"globe-trotting authors\", including Lee in his blog \"Rolf Potts' Vagabonding Blog\".<ref name=twsFebL19>{{cite news\n |author= Rolf Potts\n |title= Travel Writers\n |publisher= Rolf Potts' Vagabonding\n |quote= ...for a Pulitzer Prize for articles about Gorbachev's Russia. \n |year= 2007\n |url= http://rolfpotts.com/gary-lee/\n |accessdate= 2016-11-12\n}}</ref> Lee advises would-be travel writers to learn a foreign language to help one \"gain insight into how another culture ticks.\"<ref name=twsFebL19/> In an interview, Lee described his approach to travel writing:\n\n{{Quotation|When I arrive at a destination, I like to have a plan for what I want to focus on: music in Salvador Bahia, Brazil, art galleries in Dallas and Fort Worth, dive bars in LA, and so on. But I always grapple with how much I should stick with the plan and how much to riff, be serendipitous and follow the natural path that unwinds through every place.<ref name=twsFebL19/>|Gary Lee|Interview in Rolf Potts' \"Vagabonding\"}}\n\nAccording to the ''Washington Post'', he loves \"exotic digestibles\" such as \"mare's milk in Mongolia.\"<ref name=twsFebL14>{{cite news\n |author      = Staff writer\n |title       = Blogger Profile: Gary Lee\n |newspaper   = Washington Post\n |date        = December 8, 2006\n |url         = http://blog.washingtonpost.com/travellog/2006/12/blogger_profile_gary_lee.html\n |access-date  = 2011-02-12\n |url-status     = dead\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120614104623/http://blog.washingtonpost.com/travellog/2006/12/blogger_profile_gary_lee.html\n |archive-date = June 14, 2012\n}}</ref> In addition to his writing, Lee is co-founder and co-owner of Las Canteras Restaurant, voted the top Latin restaurant in [[Washington, D.C.]] in 2011 and 2012. He is also helped to start and is co-owner and marketing director of Casa Arequipa, a boutique hotel in [[Arequipa, Peru]] cited by Tripadvisor as one of the top 25 hotels in South America in 2012.<ref name=twsFebL15/>\n\n==Charity work and volunteering==\nLee was elected to the position of charter trustee of Phillips Academy in 2009, and helps organize events such as ''Non-sibi day'' as well as hosting and speaking at alumni events.<ref name=twsFebL15/><ref name=twsFebL16>{{cite news\n |title= Phillips Academy Names Five New Trustees\n |publisher= Phillips academy\n |date= June 30, 2009\n |url= http://www.andover.edu/About/Newsroom/Pages/newtrustees2009.aspx\n |accessdate= 2011-02-12\n}}</ref> He received Andover's \"Distinguished Service Award\" in 1998.<ref name=twsFebL16/> He's a member of the Ted Scripps Fellowships Advisory Board at the Center for [[Environmental journalism|Environmental Journalism]] at the [[University of Colorado]].<ref name=twsFebL16/>\nLee has served as a board member of the Society of Environmental Journalists.\nHe was a founder and co-chair of the newsroom diversity committee at The Washington Post.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://rolfpotts.com/gary-lee/ Gary Lee on travel writing]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Gary}}\n[[Category:Phillips Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Amherst College alumni]]\n[[Category:The Washington Post journalists]]\n[[Category:Time (magazine) people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Writers from Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Gary Lee\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_date                = <!-- {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place               = \n| death_date                = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place               = \n| education                 = [[Phillips Academy]]\n| alma_mater                = [[Amherst College]]\n| occupation                = [[journalist]],<br/>[[travel writer]]\n| years_active              = 33\n| employer                  = ''[[Washington Post]]'',<br/>''[[Time Magazine]]''\n| known_for                 = \n| notable_works             = \n| home_town                 = [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n| partner                   = \n| children                  = \n| parents                   = \n| awards                    = Lowell Thomas,<ref name=twsFebL18/>\n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| footnotes                 = \n| box_width                 = \n}}\n\n'''Gary Lee''' is an American [[journalist]] with a focus on foreign policy, [[travel writer|travel writing]] and environmental issues. He wrote for the ''[[Washington Post]]'' as well as ''[[Time Magazine]]''. He speaks five languages including [[Russian language|Russian]]<ref name=twsFebL17/> German, French and Spanish, and he was the Washington Post's Moscow Bureau Chief.<ref name=twsFebL17/><ref name=twsFebL21>{{cite news\n |author= Ken Ringle\n |title= The New Yorker's 