990s]]\n* [[List of Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one songs of the 2000s]]\n* [[List of Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one songs of the 2010s]]\n* [[List of Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one songs of the 2020s]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks Current ''Billboard'' Mainstream Rock chart]\n\n{{US Rock chart}}\n{{Billboard}}\n\n[[Category:Billboard charts]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one singles|*]]\n", "name_user": "Jacob S. Jackson", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArtists with the most number one songs:Also merged the cells for Shinedown and Three Days Grace numbers, since they both now have the same number of no. 1 songs as of the current date (04/19/2020)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mainstream_Rock_(chart)"}
{"title_page": "Voodoo Woman", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Voodoo Woman\n| image          = Voodoowoman.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = [[film poster]] by [[Albert Kallis]]\n| director       = [[Edward L. Cahn]]\n| producer       = [[Alex Gordon (writer-producer)|Alex Gordon]]\n| writer         = [[Russ Bender]]<br />[[V.I. Voss]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Marla English]]<br />[[Tom Conway]]<br />[[Mike Connors]]\n| music          = [[John Blackburn (songwriter)|John Blackburn]]<br />[[Darrell Calker]]\n| cinematography = [[Frederick E. West]]\n| editing        = [[Ronald Sinclair]]\n| distributor    = [[American International Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1957|3|1}}\n| runtime        = 75 min.\n| country        = United States \n| language       = English\n| budget         = $65,000<ref name=\"AIP\">Mark McGee, ''Faster and Furiouser: The Revised and Fattened Fable of American International Pictures'', McFarland, 1996 p74</ref>\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''Voodoo Woman''''' is a 1957 [[horror film]] directed by [[Edward L. Cahn]] and starring  [[Marla English]], [[Tom Conway]], and [[Mike Connors]]. It was released by [[American International Pictures]] as a [[double feature]] with ''[[The Undead (film)|The Undead]]''.\n\n==Plot==\n{{expand section|date=September 2014}}\nA pair of [[treasure hunters]], which includes the beautiful but ruthless Marilyn Blanchard ([[Marla English]]), discover gold in the voodoo idol of a tribe of the [[Africa]]n [[jungle]].  Hoping to find more such treasures, they [[confidence trick|con]] the innocent Ted Bronson ([[Mike Connors]]) into acting as a jungle guide and leading them to the tribe that made the idol.\n\nMeanwhile, Dr. Roland Gerard ([[Tom Conway]]), a [[mad scientist]] who has exiled himself deep in the same jungle, is using a combination of native [[Haitian Vodou|voodoo]] and his own [[biochemistry|biochemical]] discoveries in an attempt to create a superhuman being.  He hopes that this being, possessing the best of man and beast, will be the mother of a new perfect and deathless race which he will control with a mixture of [[hypnosis]] and [[telepathy]].  He is accompanied by his wife, Susan ([[Mary Ellen Kaye]]), who has long since disavowed her husband but remains trapped by her husband and the natives.\n\nDr. Gerard's initial attempts to create a female superbeing are a failure because the transformation is only temporary and the native girl used as the subject of the experiment lacks the killer instinct he deems necessary for survival.  However, when he stumbles upon the party of treasure hunters, he decides that Marilyn will be a perfect subject for his experiment.  He successfully turns her into an invulnerable monster, but her inherent selfishness and greed outweigh his mental control over her and she turns on him.  Ted and Susan are able to escape in the ensuing chaos.\n\n==Cast==\n* Marilyn Blanchard, treasure hunter - played by [[Marla English]]\n* Chaka, the [[witch doctor]] who is Gerard's partner in monster-making - played by [[Martin Wilkins]]\n* Bobo, the Gerards' native [[houseboy]] - played by [[Otis Greene]]\n* Gandor, a burly and surly native guard with a spear - played by Emmett Smith\n* Zaranda, a gentle native girl and the first victim of Gerard's evil experiment - played by [[Jean Davis]]\n* Susan Gerard, the doctor's trapped and terrified wife - played by [[Mary Ellen Kay]]\n* Rick Brady, Marilyn's cowardly killer of a boyfriend - played by [[Lance Fuller]]\n* Marcel, a good-naturedly crooked [[bar (establishment)|bar]] owner in a lawless African town - played by [[Paul Dubov]]\n* Harry West, a tough-talking treasure hunter who lets the wrong woman see a gold and gem-decorated [[voodoo doll]] - played [[Norman Willis (actor)|Norman Willis]]\n* Ted Bronson, a heroic, handsome but rather hapless jungle guide - played by [[Mike Connors|Mike \"Touch\" Connors]]\n* The Voodoo Women, an identical pair of massively mutated [[zombies]] - created and played by [[Paul Blaisdell]]\n\n==Production==\n{{expand section|date=April 2015}}\nLance Fuller reportedly had a two-films-a-year deal over five years with Golden State Productions.<ref>Desilu Feature Will Star John Bromfield; Dahl, Harvey New Team\nSchallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] 27 Oct 1956: B3.</ref>\n\nThe original make-up design for the Voodoo Woman was deemed unsuitable at the last minute and the title monster is actually the [[The She-Creature|She Creature]] costume hurriedly stripped of its tail, fins and [[pincer (biology)|pincer-like]] [[claws]].   What remained was the bulky [[Thing (comics)|Thing]]-style body, which was wrapped in a [[burlap]] [[sarong]] and topped with a modified [[skull]] [[mask]] and big [[blond]] [[wig]].  Cahn worked actively to conceal this fact, using quick cuts and keeping her mostly in shadows or behind foliage.  The rumbling growl of a [[lion]] was also [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]] for added effect.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section|date=April 2015}}\nThe film is widely regarded as one of the worst films in cinema{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} - yet in 1966, just nine years later, it was remade by [[Larry Buchanan]] into a TV film that is considered even worse, ''[[Curse of the Swamp Creature]]''.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}\n\nOn a more personal level, in his ''The Pit and the Pen'' column in ''[[Fangoria]]'' magazine producer [[Alex Gordon (writer-producer)|Alex Gordon]] revealed that the movie nearly caused a break-up with his then-[[fiance]] [[Ruth Alexander (writer)|Ruth Alexander]].  Proud of the finished production he took her to see it at its [[Burbank, California|Burbank]] premiere only to have her hand back his [[engagement ring]] when it was over, telling him that he should be making prestigious high class art films and not trash like this. Luckily, his brother [[Richard Gordon (film producer)|Richard]] was able to explain to her the differences between low budget and big budget film-making, and she and Alex were eventually married, with her later actually scripting several of his features.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1957]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0051174}}\n* {{amg movie|53021}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=94921}}\n* {{AFI film|id=52436|title=Voodoo Woman}}\n\n{{Edward L. Cahn}}\n\n[[Category:1957 horror films]]\n[[Category:1957 films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Edward Cahn]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American International Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Voodoo Woman\n| image          = Voodoowoman.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = [[film poster]] by [[Albert Kallis]]\n| director       = [[Edward L. Cahn]]\n| producer       = [[Alex Gordon (writer-producer)|Alex Gordon]]\n| writer         = [[Russ Bender]]<br />[[V.I. Voss]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Marla English]]<br />[[Tom Conway]]<br />[[Mike Connors]]\n| music          = [[John Blackburn (songwriter)|John Blackburn]]<br />[[Darrell Calker]]\n| cinematography = [[Frederick E. West]]\n| editing        = [[Ronald Sinclair]]\n| distributor    = [[American International Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1957|3|1}}\n| runtime        = 75 min.\n| country        = United States \n| language       = English\n| budget         = $65,000<ref name=\"AIP\">Mark McGee, ''Faster and Furiouser: The Revised and Fattened Fable of American International Pictures'', McFarland, 1996 p74</ref>\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''Voodoo Woman''''' is a 1957 [[horror film]] directed by [[Edward L. Cahn]] and starring  [[Marla English]], [[Tom Conway]], and [[Mike Connors]]. It was released by [[American International Pictures]] as a [[double feature]] with ''[[The Undead (film)|The Undead]]''.\n\n==Plot==\n{{expand section|date=September 2014}}\nA pair of [[treasure hunters]], which includes the beautiful but ruthless Marilyn Blanchard ([[Marla English]]), discover gold in the voodoo idol of a tribe of the [[Africa]]n [[jungle]].  Hoping to find more such treasures, they [[confidence trick|con]] the innocent Ted Bronson ([[Mike Connors]]) into acting as a jungle guide and leading them to the tribe that made the idol.\n\nMeanwhile, Dr. Roland Gerard ([[Tom Conway]]), a [[mad scientist]] who has exiled himself deep in the same jungle, is using a combination of native [[Haitian Vodou|voodoo]] and his own [[biochemistry|biochemical]] discoveries in an attempt to create a superhuman being.  He hopes that this being, possessing the best of man and beast, will be the mother of a new perfect and deathless race which he will control with a mixture of [[hypnosis]] and [[telepathy]].  He is accompanied by his wife, Susan ([[Mary Ellen Kaye]]), who has long since disavowed her husband but remains trapped by her husband and the natives.\n\nDr. Gerard's initial attempts to create a female superbeing are a failure because the transformation is only temporary and the native girl used as the subject of the experiment lacks the killer instinct he deems necessary for survival.  However, when he stumbles upon the party of treasure hunters, he decides that Marilyn will be a perfect subject for his experiment.  He successfully turns her into an invulnerable monster, but her inherent selfishness and greed outweigh his mental control over her and she turns on him.  Ted and Susan are able to escape in the ensuing chaos.\n\n==Cast==\n* Marilyn Blanchard, treasure hunter - played by [[Marla English]]\n* Chaka, the [[Witch Doctor]] who is Gerard's partner in monster-making - played by [[Martin Wilkins]]\n* Bobo, the Gerards' native [[houseboy]] - played by [[Otis Greene]]\n* Gandor, a burly and surly native guard with a spear - played by Emmett Smith\n* Zaranda, a gentle native girl and the first victim of Gerard's evil experiment - played by [[Jean Davis]]\n* Susan Gerard, the doctor's trapped and terrified wife - played by [[Mary Ellen Kay]]\n* Rick Brady, Marilyn's cowardly killer of a boyfriend - played by [[Lance Fuller]]\n* Marcel, a good-naturedly crooked [[bar (establishment)|bar]] owner in a lawless African town - played by [[Paul Dubov]]\n* Harry West, a tough-talking treasure hunter who lets the wrong woman see a gold and gem-decorated [[voodoo doll]] - played [[Norman Willis (actor)|Norman Willis]]\n* Ted Bronson, a heroic, handsome but rather hapless jungle guide - played by [[Mike Connors|Mike \"Touch\" Connors]]\n* The Voodoo Women, an identical pair of massively mutated [[zombies]] - created and played by [[Paul Blaisdell]]\n\n==Production==\n{{expand section|date=April 2015}}\nLance Fuller reportedly had a two-films-a-year deal over five years with Golden State Productions.<ref>Desilu Feature Will Star John Bromfield; Dahl, Harvey New Team\nSchallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] 27 Oct 1956: B3.</ref>\n\nThe original make-up design for the Voodoo Woman was deemed unsuitable at the last minute and the title monster is actually the [[The She-Creature|She Creature]] costume hurriedly stripped of its tail, fins and [[pincer (biology)|pincer-like]] [[claws]].   What remained was the bulky [[Thing (comics)|Thing]]-style body, which was wrapped in a [[burlap]] [[sarong]] and topped with a modified [[skull]] [[mask]] and big [[blond]] [[wig]].  Cahn worked actively to conceal this fact, using quick cuts and keeping her mostly in shadows or behind foliage.  The rumbling growl of a [[lion]] was also [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]] for added effect.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section|date=April 2015}}\nThe film is widely regarded as one of the worst films in cinema{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} - yet in 1966, just nine years later, it was remade by [[Larry Buchanan]] into a TV film that is considered even worse, ''[[Curse of the Swamp Creature]]''.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}\n\nOn a more personal level, in his ''The Pit and the Pen'' column in ''[[Fangoria]]'' magazine producer [[Alex Gordon (writer-producer)|Alex Gordon]] revealed that the movie nearly caused a break-up with his then-[[fiance]] [[Ruth Alexander (writer)|Ruth Alexander]].  Proud of the finished production he took her to see it at its [[Burbank, California|Burbank]] premiere only to have her hand back his [[engagement ring]] when it was over, telling him that he should be making prestigious high class art films and not trash like this. Luckily, his brother [[Richard Gordon (film producer)|Richard]] was able to explain to her the differences between low budget and big budget film-making, and she and Alex were eventually married, with her later actually scripting several of his features.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1957]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0051174}}\n* {{amg movie|53021}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=94921}}\n* {{AFI film|id=52436|title=Voodoo Woman}}\n\n{{Edward L. Cahn}}\n\n[[Category:1957 horror films]]\n[[Category:1957 films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Edward Cahn]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American International Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast:lower case", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voodoo_Woman"}
{"title_page": "Nate Lee", "text_new": "{{for|the Guamanian footballer|Nate Lee (footballer)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Nate Lee\n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|alt           = \n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = \n|birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1956}}\n|birth_place   = \n|death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|death_place   = \n|death_cause   = \n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|residence     = \n|nationality   = American\n|ethnicity     = \n|citizenship   = \n|other_names   = \n|known_for     = \n|education     = [[Phillips Academy|Andover]]\n|alma_mater    = [[Tulane University|Tulane]]\n|employer      = \n|occupation    = writer\n|years_active  = \n|home_town     = \n|awards        = \n|signature     = \n|website       = \n|footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Nate Lee''' is an American author<ref name=twsOctI22 /> and former [[senior editor]] at [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago's]] ''[[Newcity]]'' weekly magazine<ref name=twsOctI14>{{cite news\n |author= Staff writer\n |title= Performance Advertising: Theater, Dance, Comedy, Opera\n |publisher= NewCity Network\n |date= October 2009\n |url= http://newcitynetwork.com/advertising-marketing/performance-advertising-theater-dance-comedy-opera/\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctI13>{{cite news\n |title       = Bibliography\n |publisher   = Rainer Spangl\n |quote       = Bibliography Nate Lee, \"Little Triggers\", Newcity, June 2009\n |date        = June 2009\n |url         = http://rainerspangl.com/about/cv/\n |accessdate  = October 31, 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110715151026/http://rainerspangl.com/about/cv/\n |archivedate = July 15, 2011\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref> who advocated passionately for [[live theater]].<ref name=twsOctI15>{{cite news\n |author= Brian Hieggelke\n |title= Back through the Lookingglass\n |publisher= NewCity Stage\n |quote= ... Newcity's first senior editor Nate Lee penned a cover story that November, as the production moved from the confines of Chicago Filmmakers to the larger space inhabited by Remains Theatre. In the process of reporting, he insisted I see it and took me along. It was unforgettable, and probably had much to do with our growing and sustained commitment to theater coverage. (Though in fairness, Nate's passion for Chicago theater, or theatre, as he insisted, from our very first issues set the pace from day one.)\n |date= June 5, 2009\n |url= http://newcitystage.com/2009/06/05/back-through-the-lookingglass/\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctI21>{{cite news\n |author= Nate Lee\n |title= Romper Room: Back flips, harem girls and the secret of life from the Lookingglass Theatre Company\n |publisher= NewCity Stage\n |quote= The critics agree, as they say. If I were to add my own voice to the shouts of praises for Lookingglass Theatre and their current hit play, \"Arabian Nights,\" I believe I'd use ancient words like \"kaleidoscopic phantasmagoria.\u201d\n |date= November 12, 2009\n |url= http://newcitystage.com/1992/11/12/romper-room-back-flips-harem-girls-and-the-secret-of-life-from-the-lookingglass-theatre-company/\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref> At Newcity, Lee wrote features, a weekly column called ''Urbanitie'', theatre and film reviews as well as stories on architecture and [[historic preservation]], and at one point wrote a book which turned into a [[musical comedy]] revue entitled ''Speak of the Twenties''.<ref name=twsNovC14>{{cite web\n |title= CHORAL-VOCAL WORKS AND STAGE WORKS\n |publisher= anything sung\n |quote= Speak of the Twenties, A Musical Comedy Revue . Book by Nate Lee. 50' Commissioned by Barron Productions. Performed in 1989 at Holstein's and The Gaslight, Chicago, IL. Subsequent runs at various Chicago venues through 1991.\n |year= 1989\n |url= http://web.me.com/brian.wilson/Site/Choral,_Vocal_and_Stage_Works.html\n |accessdate= November 3, 2010\n}}</ref> Working with publishers Brian and Jan Hieggelke, he attracted top writers to write for Newcity including top theater critics who became prominent at other publications later, including Chris Jones of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' and Rohan Preston of the ''[[Minneapolis Star-Tribune]]''.<ref name=twsOctI14/> He wrote numerous books published by Abingdon Press<ref name=twsOctI22/> and reviews for websites.<ref name=twsOctI998>{{cite web\n |author= Nate Lee\n |title= Stanley Kubrick\n |publisher= MovieDirectors.com\n |quote= 2010 \u2013 An obsessive-compulsive auteur, Kubrick was purposely enigmatic with his work, yet disdained the many rumors about his eccentricity.... \n |date= November 4, 2010\n |url= http://topmoviedirectors.com/stanley_kubrick.htm\n |accessdate= November 4, 2010\n}}</ref> Lee attended [[Phillips Academy]] in [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]] and graduated in the school's first co\u2013educational class in 1974 along with classmates jazz Grammy\u2013winner [[Bill Cunliffe]], actor [[Dana Delany]], poet [[Karl Kirchwey]], editor [[Sara Nelson (editor)|Sara Nelson]], and sculptor [[Gar Waterman]]; Lee and painter [[Julian Hatton]] were close friends and studied [[Latin (language)|Latin]] at Andover. At present, he lives in California, writes and edits for [[Demand Studios]], and works in advertising.\n\n==Publications==\n* Words From the Cross and 5 Other Dramas for Tweens, by Nate Lee (Paperback) 2010<ref name=twsOctI22>{{cite news\n |title= List of Books by Nate Lee\n |publisher= Paperback Swap\n |quote= 2010 \u2013 Words From the Cross and 5 Other Dramas for Tweens (Paperback) 2007 \u2013 What a Story!: And Five Other Dramas for Tweens (Paperback) 2006 \u2013 Don't Miss the Bus and five Other Dramas for Tweens (Paperback) 2005 -... \n |date= October 31, 2010\n |url= http://www.paperbackswap.com/Nate-Lee/author/\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref>\n* What a Story!: And Five Other Dramas for Tweens, by Nate Lee (Paperback) 2007\n* Don't Miss the Bus and five Other Dramas for Tweens, by Nate Lee, published by Abingdon Press (2006) {{ISBN|978-0-687-33098-0}}<ref name=twsOctI25>{{cite news\n |author= Nate Lee\n |title= Don't Miss the Bus: And 5 Other Dramas for Tweens (Hardcover)\n |publisher= Amazon\n |quote= # Reading level: Ages 9\u201312 Hardcover: 48 pages Publisher: Abingdon Press (June 2006) Language: English {{ISBN|0-687-33098-X}} {{ISBN|978-0-687-33098-0}} \n |date= June 2006\n |url= https://www.amazon.com/Dont-Miss-Bus-Dramas-Tweens/dp/068733098X/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1288549386&sr=1-1\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref>\n* I'll Be Right Back And 5 Other Dramas for Tweens, by Nate Lee<ref name=twsOctI22/>\n* What's The Score: And 5 Other Drams For Teens (Paperback)<ref name=twsOctI22/>\n* Trouble in the Temple And Five Other Dramas for Tweens (Paperback)<ref name=twsOctI22/>\n* Sleep On It!: And 5 Other Dramas for Tweens, by Nate Lee (Hardcover), Abingdon Press, (2007) {{ISBN|978-0-687-49178-0}}<ref name=twsOctI31>{{cite news\n |author= Nate Lee\n |title= Sleep on It!: And 5 Other Dramas for Tweens (Hardcover)\n |publisher= Amazon\n |quote= # Publisher: Abingdon Press (December 2007) Language: English {{ISBN|0-687-49178-9}} {{ISBN|978-0-687-49178-0}}\n |date= December 2007\n |url= https://www.amazon.com/Sleep-5-Other-Dramas-Tweens/dp/0687491789/ref=ntt_at_ep_dpi_1\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref>\n* Joy in the Morning: Easy Dramas, Speeches, and Recitations for Children (Paperback)<ref name=twsOctI22/>\n* Gift of Christmas Presence (Paperback)<ref name=twsOctI22/>\n* The Invitation: And 5 Other Dramas for Tweens, by Nate Lee<ref name=twsOctI23>{{cite news\n |author= Nate Lee\n |title= The Invitation: And 5 Other Dramas for Tweens\n |publisher= Family Christian Stores\n |date= October 31, 2010\n |url= http://www.familychristian.com/shop/product.asp?prodID=87237&name=-\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Demand Media}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Nate}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American theater critics]]\n[[Category:Christian writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Phillips Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Guamanian footballer|Nate Lee (footballer)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Nate Lee\n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|alt           = \n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = \n|birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1956}}\n|birth_place   = \n|death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|death_place   = \n|death_cause   = \n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|residence     = \n|nationality   = American\n|ethnicity     = \n|citizenship   = \n|other_names   = \n|known_for     = \n|education     = [[Phillips Academy|Andover]]\n|alma_mater    = [[Tulane University|Tulane]]\n|employer      = \n|occupation    = writer\n|years_active  = \n|home_town     = \n|awards        = \n|signature     = \n|website       = \n|footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Nate Lee''' is an American author<ref name=twsOctI22 /> and former [[senior editor]] at [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago's]] ''[[Newcity]]'' weekly magazine<ref name=twsOctI14>{{cite news\n |author= Staff writer\n |title= Performance Advertising: Theater, Dance, Comedy, Opera\n |publisher= NewCity Network\n |date= October 2009\n |url= http://newcitynetwork.com/advertising-marketing/performance-advertising-theater-dance-comedy-opera/\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctI13>{{cite news\n |title       = Bibliography\n |publisher   = Rainer Spangl\n |quote       = Bibliography Nate Lee, \"Little Triggers\", Newcity, June 2009\n |date        = June 2009\n |url         = http://rainerspangl.com/about/cv/\n |accessdate  = October 31, 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110715151026/http://rainerspangl.com/about/cv/\n |archivedate = July 15, 2011\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref> who advocated passionately for [[live theater]].<ref name=twsOctI15>{{cite news\n |author= Brian Hieggelke\n |title= Back through the Lookingglass\n |publisher= NewCity Stage\n |quote= ... Newcity's first senior editor Nate Lee penned a cover story that November, as the production moved from the confines of Chicago Filmmakers to the larger space inhabited by Remains Theatre. In the process of reporting, he insisted I see it and took me along. It was unforgettable, and probably had much to do with our growing and sustained commitment to theater coverage. (Though in fairness, Nate's passion for Chicago theater, or theatre, as he insisted, from our very first issues set the pace from day one.)\n |date= June 5, 2009\n |url= http://newcitystage.com/2009/06/05/back-through-the-lookingglass/\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctI21>{{cite news\n |author= Nate Lee\n |title= Romper Room: Back flips, harem girls and the secret of life from the Lookingglass Theatre Company\n |publisher= NewCity Stage\n |quote= The critics agree, as they say. If I were to add my own voice to the shouts of praises for Lookingglass Theatre and their current hit play, \"Arabian Nights,\" I believe I'd use ancient words like \"kaleidoscopic phantasmagoria.\u201d\n |date= November 12, 2009\n |url= http://newcitystage.com/1992/11/12/romper-room-back-flips-harem-girls-and-the-secret-of-life-from-the-lookingglass-theatre-company/\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref> At Newcity, Lee wrote features, a weekly column called ''Urbanitie'', theatre and film reviews as well as stories on architecture and [[historic preservation]], and at one point wrote a book which turned into a [[musical comedy]] revue entitled ''Speak of the Twenties''.<ref name=twsNovC14>{{cite web\n |title= CHORAL-VOCAL WORKS AND STAGE WORKS\n |publisher= anything sung\n |quote= Speak of the Twenties, A Musical Comedy Revue . Book by Nate Lee. 50' Commissioned by Barron Productions. Performed in 1989 at Holstein's and The Gaslight, Chicago, IL. Subsequent runs at various Chicago venues through 1991.\n |year= 1989\n |url= http://web.me.com/brian.wilson/Site/Choral,_Vocal_and_Stage_Works.html\n |accessdate= November 3, 2010\n}}</ref> Working with publishers Brian and Jan Hieggelke, he attracted top writers to write for Newcity including top theater critics who became prominent at other publications later, including Chris Jones of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' and Rohan Preston of the ''[[Minneapolis Star-Tribune]]''.<ref name=twsOctI14/> He wrote numerous books published by Abingdon Press<ref name=twsOctI22/> and reviews for websites.<ref name=twsOctI998>{{cite web\n |author= Nate Lee\n |title= Stanley Kubrick\n |publisher= MovieDirectors.com\n |quote= 2010 \u2013 An obsessive-compulsive auteur, Kubrick was purposely enigmatic with his work, yet disdained the many rumors about his eccentricity.... \n |date= November 4, 2010\n |url= http://topmoviedirectors.com/stanley_kubrick.htm\n |accessdate= November 4, 2010\n}}</ref> Lee attended [[Phillips Academy]] in [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]] and graduated in the school's first co\u2013educational class in 1974 along with classmates jazz Grammy\u2013winner [[Bill Cunliffe]], actor [[Dana Delany]], poet [[Karl Kirchwey]], editor [[Sara Nelson]], and sculptor [[Gar Waterman]]; Lee and painter [[Julian Hatton]] were close friends and studied [[Latin (language)|Latin]] at Andover. At present, he lives in California, writes and edits for [[Demand Studios]], and works in advertising.\n\n==Publications==\n* Words From the Cross and 5 Other Dramas for Tweens, by Nate Lee (Paperback) 2010<ref name=twsOctI22>{{cite news\n |title= List of Books by Nate Lee\n |publisher= Paperback Swap\n |quote= 2010 \u2013 Words From the Cross and 5 Other Dramas for Tweens (Paperback) 2007 \u2013 What a Story!: And Five Other Dramas for Tweens (Paperback) 2006 \u2013 Don't Miss the Bus and five Other Dramas for Tweens (Paperback) 2005 -... \n |date= October 31, 2010\n |url= http://www.paperbackswap.com/Nate-Lee/author/\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref>\n* What a Story!: And Five Other Dramas for Tweens, by Nate Lee (Paperback) 2007\n* Don't Miss the Bus and five Other Dramas for Tweens, by Nate Lee, published by Abingdon Press (2006) {{ISBN|978-0-687-33098-0}}<ref name=twsOctI25>{{cite news\n |author= Nate Lee\n |title= Don't Miss the Bus: And 5 Other Dramas for Tweens (Hardcover)\n |publisher= Amazon\n |quote= # Reading level: Ages 9\u201312 Hardcover: 48 pages Publisher: Abingdon Press (June 2006) Language: English {{ISBN|0-687-33098-X}} {{ISBN|978-0-687-33098-0}} \n |date= June 2006\n |url= https://www.amazon.com/Dont-Miss-Bus-Dramas-Tweens/dp/068733098X/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1288549386&sr=1-1\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref>\n* I'll Be Right Back And 5 Other Dramas for Tweens, by Nate Lee<ref name=twsOctI22/>\n* What's The Score: And 5 Other Drams For Teens (Paperback)<ref name=twsOctI22/>\n* Trouble in the Temple And Five Other Dramas for Tweens (Paperback)<ref name=twsOctI22/>\n* Sleep On It!: And 5 Other Dramas for Tweens, by Nate Lee (Hardcover), Abingdon Press, (2007) {{ISBN|978-0-687-49178-0}}<ref name=twsOctI31>{{cite news\n |author= Nate Lee\n |title= Sleep on It!: And 5 Other Dramas for Tweens (Hardcover)\n |publisher= Amazon\n |quote= # Publisher: Abingdon Press (December 2007) Language: English {{ISBN|0-687-49178-9}} {{ISBN|978-0-687-49178-0}}\n |date= December 2007\n |url= https://www.amazon.com/Sleep-5-Other-Dramas-Tweens/dp/0687491789/ref=ntt_at_ep_dpi_1\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref>\n* Joy in the Morning: Easy Dramas, Speeches, and Recitations for Children (Paperback)<ref name=twsOctI22/>\n* Gift of Christmas Presence (Paperback)<ref name=twsOctI22/>\n* The Invitation: And 5 Other Dramas for Tweens, by Nate Lee<ref name=twsOctI23>{{cite news\n |author= Nate Lee\n |title= The Invitation: And 5 Other Dramas for Tweens\n |publisher= Family Christian Stores\n |date= October 31, 2010\n |url= http://www.familychristian.com/shop/product.asp?prodID=87237&name=-\n |accessdate= October 31, 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Demand Media}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Nate}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American theater critics]]\n[[Category:Christian writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Phillips Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSara Nelson(link changed toSara Nelson (editor)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nate_Lee"}
{"title_page": "Priscilla Martel", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox chef <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox chef/doc]] -->\n| name = Priscilla Martel\n| image = Priscilla Martel.jpg\n| caption = Priscilla Martel\n| birth_name  = Priscilla Martel\n| birth_date  ={{birth date and age|1956|10|22}}\n| birth_place = \n| style = [[Mediterranean cuisine|Mediterranean]]\n| education = [[Phillips Academy|Andover]]<br>[[Brown University]]\n| spouse = Charlie van Over\n| ratings =\n| restaurants = All About Food\n| television = \n| prevrests = Restaurant du Village<br><small>1979&ndash;1990</small><br>[[Chester, Connecticut|Chester]], [[Connecticut|CT]]\n| website ={{url|priscillamartel.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Priscilla Martel''' is an award-winning<ref name=twsOctN34/> American chef, food writer, and consultant notable for desserts, [[baking]], [[pastry|pastries]] and [[fireplace]]-cooked meals. Her recipes appear in magazines such as ''[[Food & Wine]].'' She is a contributing writer at ''Flavor and the Menu'' Magazine.<ref name=twsOctN13>{{cite news\n |title= sentimental sweets\n |publisher= Flavor-Trends\n |quote= ... Diners will want to see which version they like better.Priscilla Martel (see page 108)\n |year= 2010\n |url= http://www.dealtime.com/Book_On_Cooking_A_Testbook_Of_Culinary_Fundamentals_Sarah_Labensky_Alan_M_Hause_Steven_Labensky_Priscilla_Martel/info\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctN12>{{cite news\n |author= Priscilla Martel\n |title= Rustic Revolution\n |publisher= Flavor Trends\n |quote= Big Dish: Clay pots, skillets, pottery and pot pies served at the table are less-fancy ways to present this rustic fare. \u2014 PRISCILLA MARTEL\n |year= 2010\n |url= http://www.flavor-trends.com/article1_2.asp?artKy=9396281\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> She teaches and has written [[textbooks]] including [[ebook]]s<ref name=twsOctN21>{{cite news\n |author1=Sarah R. Labensky |author2=Priscilla A. Martel |author3=Alan M. Hause |title= Pearson eText for On Cooking: A Textbook of Culinary Fundamentals, 5/E \n |publisher= Pearson Higher Education\n |quote= Format: Electronic Book; 1320 pp\n |date= March 19, 2010\n |url= http://vig.pearsonhighered.com/educator/academic/product/0,3110,0138021864,00.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> used to teach students of the [[culinary arts]].<ref name=twsOctN22>{{cite news\n |author1=Sarah R. Labensky |author2=Priscilla A. Martel |author3=Alan M. Hause |title= Pearson Test Kitchen for On Cooking: A Textbook of Culinary Fundamentals, 5/E \n |publisher= Pearson Higher Education\n |quote= Sarah R. Labensky, Priscilla A. Martel, Alan M. Hause, Fabulous Food\n |date= February 8, 2010\n |url= http://vig.pearsonhighered.com/educator/academic/product/0,3110,013510887X,00.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> She is recognized as an authority on artisan baking, confectionery, cooking food in sealed plastic bags with water or steam called [[sous vide]], and spa cooking techniques.<ref name=\"twsNHReg\">{{cite news \n| author= Stephen Fries\n| date= January 5, 2016\n| newspaper= New Haven Register\n| url= http://www.nhregister.com/article/NH/20160105/NEWS/160109805\n| title= 2016 food forecast: farro, fermented fare, savory yogurts, boozy desserts\n| accessdate= February 11, 2016\n| quote=...Martel ... is an expert in artisan baking, confectionery, sous vide (food sealed in plastic bags and cooked in a water bath or by steam) and spa cooking techniques....\n}}</ref> In 2016, Martel is teaching a course in food writing at GateWay Community College in New Haven.<ref name=\"twsNHReg\"/>\n\nMartel married prominent Connecticut restaurateur and chef Charlie van Over, and the couple often collaborate on recipes and cooking. Martel and van Over have cooked for ''[[60 Minutes]]'' reporter [[Morley Safer]], Chef [[Jacques Pepin]] as well as [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] actor [[Peter Kapetan]] at their home in [[Connecticut]].<ref name=twsOctN23/> Martel and van Over were co&ndash;owners of a restaurant in [[Chester, Connecticut|Chester]] called Restaurant du Village.<ref name=twsOctN24>{{cite news\n |author= CAROLYN BATTISTA\n |title= Chefs Hunt Up a Delicious Time in Chester\n |newspaper= The New York Times\n |quote= 'You have a busy kitchen, Charlie,'' he said to Charles van Over, the co-owner of the Restaurant du Village, with Priscilla Martel. Mr. van Over was cooking sausage in a pan.\n |date= January 1, 1989\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1989/01/01/nyregion/chefs-hunt-up-a-delicious-time-in-chester.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> Her cooking often reflects a [[Mediterranean cuisine|Mediterranean]] emphasis.<ref name=twsOctN25>{{cite news\n |author= MOIRA HODGSON\n |title= THE SETTING IS CHESTER, CONN., BUT IT looks like Provence.\n |newspaper= The New York Times\n |quote= Our menus revolve around the sort of food you get around the Mediterranean,\" says Mr. van Over.\n |date= May 31, 1992\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1992/05/31/magazine/provencal-picnic.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> She has a particular interest and expertise in almonds and desserts of the [[Northeastern United States|northeast]]. Martel and van Over hold patents regarding [[baking]] processes.<ref name=twsOctN34>{{cite news\n |title= PRISCILLA MARTEL\n |publisher= Flavor Trends\n |quote= Priscilla Martel ... holds several baking patents and collaborates with food manufacturers and restaurants to create innovative products, menus and marketing programs. \n |year= 2010\n |url= http://www.flavor-trends.com/flavor_experts.asp\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Homar 3.jpg|thumb|left|Martel and van Over cook in a style sometimes described as [[Mediterranean cuisine]].]]\nMartel attended [[Phillips Academy]] in [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]] and graduated in the school's first co&ndash;educational class in 1974. Her classmates included jazz Grammy&ndash;winner [[Bill Cunliffe]], software financier [[Peter Currie (businessman)|Peter Currie]], actor [[Dana Delany]], painter [[Julian Hatton]], poet [[Karl Kirchwey]], writer [[Nate Lee]], television producer [[Jonathan Meath]], editor [[Sara Nelson (editor)|Sara Nelson]], and sculptor [[Gar Waterman]]. She graduated from [[Brown University]] in 1978. Her love of writing was influenced in part after taking a course at [[Wesleyan University|Wesleyan]] called ''Portraits of People'' taught by Anne Greene, in the 1980s.<ref name=\"twsNHI\"/>\n\nMartel and van Over opened a [[Chester, Connecticut]] restaurant which they named ''Restaurant du Village'' in 1979 and sold it in 1990.<ref name=twsOctN32>{{cite news\n |author= LARY BLOOM\n |title= Lessons From the Founding Fireplaces \n |newspaper= The New York Times\n |quote= It\u2019s true that Mr. Van Over, at 70, has been much more widely known for his advice in the kitchen than other parts of the house. He served as a restaurant consultant even before he and his wife, Priscilla Martel, opened Restaurant du Village, which helped make Chester a destination. (They sold it in 1990). \n |date= February 10, 2008\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/10/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/10colct.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> In 2010, they own a firm called \"All About Food\" which holds baking patents and collaborates with food manufacturers and restaurants on such matters as menus, marketing programs, and new products.<ref name=twsOctN34/>\n\n[[File:Fireplace Burning.jpg|thumb|right|Martel and van Over have friends for dinner and often cook in a [[fireplace]] and outdoor wood&ndash;fired oven.]]\nMartel and van Over were quoted in the ''[[New York Times]]'' about doing [[rotisserie]] cooking using a [[fireplace]]; on occasions, Martel and van Over have cooked for fellow Chester resident and ''[[60 Minutes]]'' reporter [[Morley Safer]].<ref name=twsOctN23>{{cite news\n |author= ELIZABETH MAKER\n |title= CONNECTICUT AT ITS BEST; On an Open Fire, Much More Than Chestnuts\n |newspaper= The New York Times\n |quote= Charlie van Over of Chester,... wife, Priscilla Martel, throw in fall and winter for guests who include Morley Safer of ''60 Minutes'' and the chef Jacques P?n, both of whom live in Chester. '... the Broadway actor Peter Kapetan, ...\n |date= December 11, 2005\n |url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F05E0D61131F932A25751C1A9639C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> The couple would cook a multicourse meal in the fireplace while having sing&ndash;a&ndash;longs which sometimes included dancing, and their dinners often included [[quail]], duck, [[venison]] or [[porterhouse steak]].<ref name=twsOctN23/> At one point, Martel and van Over lived in a house with six<ref name=twsOctN32/> or seven fireplaces.<ref name=twsOctN23/> Martel said the fireplace cooking experiences \"brings out the best in people.\"<ref name=twsOctN23/> They grow vegetables and other foods in their garden for some of their meals.<ref name=twsOctN25/> The dining table often has beautiful flowers such as [[zinnia]]s and [[Antirrhinum|snapdragons]] and meals are often served with wine.<ref name=twsOctN25/> Martel and van Over advise restaurants about such matters as how to create a [[brasserie]].<ref name=twsOctN31>{{cite news\n |author= STEPHANIE LYNESS\n |title= A New Brasserie That Knows What It Is \n |newspaper= The New York Times\n |quote= ... (Mr. Van Over, a Connecticut  chef and the original owner, with his wife, Priscilla Martel, of Restaurant du Village in Chester, was a consultant on the creation of the brasserie.) \n |date= October 14, 2006\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/14/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/15ctdine.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> Beef steak and veal stew are cooked using a Tuscan grill.<ref name=twsOctN32/> Martel and van Over argued in their book \"The Best Bread Ever\" that the best way to make the perfect loaf is to use a [[food processor]].<ref name=twsOctN32/> Martel's recipes entitled ''Cod with creamy nut sauce'' and ''Chicken Almond Curry with Apricots'' appeared in ''[[Food & Wine]]'' magazine.<ref name=twsOctN15>{{cite news\n |author= Priscilla Martel\n |title= Recipe search\n |publisher= Food and Wine\n |date= October 20, 2010\n |url= http://www.foodandwine.com/search/recipe.cfm?title=&chef=Priscilla+Martel&ingredient=&type=Entree&recipe_ethnic=&holiday_occasion=&cooking_method=&servings=&seasons=&pub_month=&pub_year=&search_submit=Submit+Query&per=25\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> She is co-author of culinary textbooks ''On Baking: A Textbook of Baking and Pastry Fundamentals'' and ''On Cooking: A Textbook of Culinary Fundamentals''.<ref name=\"twsNHReg\"/> She works as a consultant in product development to create international seafood chowders and Italian regional soups for [[Borden Milk Products|Borden]].<ref name=\"twsNHReg\"/> For [[Absolut Vodka]], she is a spokesperson and developer of recipes.<ref name=\"twsNHReg\"/> She wrote over 150 columns entitled ''All About Food'' in Connecticut newspapers.<ref name=\"twsNHI\">{{cite web \n| author= LUCY GELLMAN\n| date= January 26, 2016\n| publisher= New Haven Independent\n| url= http://www.newhavenindependent.org/index.php/archives/entry/food_writing_comes_to_gateway/\n| title= Food Writer Cooks Up A Gateway Course\n| accessdate= February 11, 2016\n| quote=...By the time Priscilla Martel took Anne Greene\u2019s \u201cPortraits of People,\u201d a creative nonfiction course taught at Wesleyan University in the 1980s...\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Almond and Mixed Berry Shortcakes by Priscilla Martel.jpg|thumb|right|Martel created the recipe for this dessert entitled \"Almond and Mixed Berry Shortcakes\". For recipe, see external links.]]\n\n==Publications==\n* ''On Baking: A Textbook of Baking and Pastry Fundamentals,'' by Sarah Labensky, Priscilla Martel and Eddy Vandamme {{ISBN|978-0-13-157923-1}}\n* ''Sampler Companion Website for On Baking: A Textbook of Baking and Pastry Fundamentals'' {{ISBN|978-0-13-504653-1}}<ref name=twsOctN11>{{cite news\n |author= Priscilla Martel\n |title= Sampler Companion Website for On Baking: A Textbook of Baking and Pastry Fundamentals\n |publisher= Pearson Higher Education\n |year= 2009\n |url= http://vig.pearsonhighered.com/educator/academic/product/0,3110,013504653X,00.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref>\n* ''On Cooking: A Textbook Of Culinary Fundamentals'', by Sarah Labensky, Alan M. Hause, Steven Labensky, Priscilla Martel; book/CD <ref name=twsOctN14>{{cite news\n |title= On cooking\n |publisher= otoku-money\n |quote= Mastercook cd for on cooking, 4/e; sarah r. labensky; alan m. hause, fabulous food; steven r. labensky; priscilla a. martel, the center for the culinary arts; ...\n |year= 2010\n |url= http://otoku-money.info/uvplm9/xnfpb.php?on-cooking-a-textbook-labensky\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref>\n* ''The Best Bread Ever: Great Homemade Bread Using Your Food Processor'' by Charles van Over and Priscilla Martel (1997)<ref name=twsOctN33>{{cite news\n |author= Charles van Over and Priscilla Martel (authors)\n |title= The Best Bread Ever\n |publisher= Bookstores.com\n |quote= The Best Bread Ever: Great Homemade Bread Using Your Food Processor (1st Edition)\n |year= 1997\n |url= http://www.allbookstores.com/Priscilla-Martel/author\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110709014938/http://www.dessertprofessional.com/profile/PriscillaMartel Martel dessert page]\n* [http://lovenbake.com/cookbook/popup.php?sb_id=115 Almond and Mixed Berry Shortcakes] online recipe posted by Priscilla Martel\n* [http://www.pearsonhighered.com/product?ISBN=0133458555 On Cooking Update] textbook by Martel, Labensky and Hause\n* [http://www.gourmetretailer.com/article-crafting_promotions-7124.html Article by Martel] in ''The Gourmet Retailer''\n* [http://www.gatewayct.edu/Offices-Departments/Public-Affairs/News/News-Items/Author-Priscilla-Martel-to-Teach-Food-Writing-Cour Author Priscilla Martel to Teach Food Writing Course] announcement\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martel, Priscilla}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Phillips Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:American restaurateurs]]\n[[Category:Women restaurateurs]]\n[[Category:American chefs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox chef <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox chef/doc]] -->\n| name = Priscilla Martel\n| image = Priscilla Martel.jpg\n| caption = Priscilla Martel\n| birth_name  = Priscilla Martel\n| birth_date  ={{birth date and age|1956|10|22}}\n| birth_place = \n| style = [[Mediterranean cuisine|Mediterranean]]\n| education = [[Phillips Academy|Andover]]<br>[[Brown University]]\n| spouse = Charlie van Over\n| ratings =\n| restaurants = All About Food\n| television = \n| prevrests = Restaurant du Village<br><small>1979&ndash;1990</small><br>[[Chester, Connecticut|Chester]], [[Connecticut|CT]]\n| website ={{url|priscillamartel.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Priscilla Martel''' is an award-winning<ref name=twsOctN34/> American chef, food writer, and consultant notable for desserts, [[baking]], [[pastry|pastries]] and [[fireplace]]-cooked meals. Her recipes appear in magazines such as ''[[Food & Wine]].'' She is a contributing writer at ''Flavor and the Menu'' Magazine.<ref name=twsOctN13>{{cite news\n |title= sentimental sweets\n |publisher= Flavor-Trends\n |quote= ... Diners will want to see which version they like better.Priscilla Martel (see page 108)\n |year= 2010\n |url= http://www.dealtime.com/Book_On_Cooking_A_Testbook_Of_Culinary_Fundamentals_Sarah_Labensky_Alan_M_Hause_Steven_Labensky_Priscilla_Martel/info\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctN12>{{cite news\n |author= Priscilla Martel\n |title= Rustic Revolution\n |publisher= Flavor Trends\n |quote= Big Dish: Clay pots, skillets, pottery and pot pies served at the table are less-fancy ways to present this rustic fare. \u2014 PRISCILLA MARTEL\n |year= 2010\n |url= http://www.flavor-trends.com/article1_2.asp?artKy=9396281\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> She teaches and has written [[textbooks]] including [[ebook]]s<ref name=twsOctN21>{{cite news\n |author1=Sarah R. Labensky |author2=Priscilla A. Martel |author3=Alan M. Hause |title= Pearson eText for On Cooking: A Textbook of Culinary Fundamentals, 5/E \n |publisher= Pearson Higher Education\n |quote= Format: Electronic Book; 1320 pp\n |date= March 19, 2010\n |url= http://vig.pearsonhighered.com/educator/academic/product/0,3110,0138021864,00.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> used to teach students of the [[culinary arts]].<ref name=twsOctN22>{{cite news\n |author1=Sarah R. Labensky |author2=Priscilla A. Martel |author3=Alan M. Hause |title= Pearson Test Kitchen for On Cooking: A Textbook of Culinary Fundamentals, 5/E \n |publisher= Pearson Higher Education\n |quote= Sarah R. Labensky, Priscilla A. Martel, Alan M. Hause, Fabulous Food\n |date= February 8, 2010\n |url= http://vig.pearsonhighered.com/educator/academic/product/0,3110,013510887X,00.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> She is recognized as an authority on artisan baking, confectionery, cooking food in sealed plastic bags with water or steam called [[sous vide]], and spa cooking techniques.<ref name=\"twsNHReg\">{{cite news \n| author= Stephen Fries\n| date= January 5, 2016\n| newspaper= New Haven Register\n| url= http://www.nhregister.com/article/NH/20160105/NEWS/160109805\n| title= 2016 food forecast: farro, fermented fare, savory yogurts, boozy desserts\n| accessdate= February 11, 2016\n| quote=...Martel ... is an expert in artisan baking, confectionery, sous vide (food sealed in plastic bags and cooked in a water bath or by steam) and spa cooking techniques....\n}}</ref> In 2016, Martel is teaching a course in food writing at GateWay Community College in New Haven.<ref name=\"twsNHReg\"/>\n\nMartel married prominent Connecticut restaurateur and chef Charlie van Over, and the couple often collaborate on recipes and cooking. Martel and van Over have cooked for ''[[60 Minutes]]'' reporter [[Morley Safer]], Chef [[Jacques Pepin]] as well as [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] actor [[Peter Kapetan]] at their home in [[Connecticut]].<ref name=twsOctN23/> Martel and van Over were co&ndash;owners of a restaurant in [[Chester, Connecticut|Chester]] called Restaurant du Village.<ref name=twsOctN24>{{cite news\n |author= CAROLYN BATTISTA\n |title= Chefs Hunt Up a Delicious Time in Chester\n |newspaper= The New York Times\n |quote= 'You have a busy kitchen, Charlie,'' he said to Charles van Over, the co-owner of the Restaurant du Village, with Priscilla Martel. Mr. van Over was cooking sausage in a pan.\n |date= January 1, 1989\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1989/01/01/nyregion/chefs-hunt-up-a-delicious-time-in-chester.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> Her cooking often reflects a [[Mediterranean cuisine|Mediterranean]] emphasis.<ref name=twsOctN25>{{cite news\n |author= MOIRA HODGSON\n |title= THE SETTING IS CHESTER, CONN., BUT IT looks like Provence.\n |newspaper= The New York Times\n |quote= Our menus revolve around the sort of food you get around the Mediterranean,\" says Mr. van Over.\n |date= May 31, 1992\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1992/05/31/magazine/provencal-picnic.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> She has a particular interest and expertise in almonds and desserts of the [[Northeastern United States|northeast]]. Martel and van Over hold patents regarding [[baking]] processes.<ref name=twsOctN34>{{cite news\n |title= PRISCILLA MARTEL\n |publisher= Flavor Trends\n |quote= Priscilla Martel ... holds several baking patents and collaborates with food manufacturers and restaurants to create innovative products, menus and marketing programs. \n |year= 2010\n |url= http://www.flavor-trends.com/flavor_experts.asp\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Homar 3.jpg|thumb|left|Martel and van Over cook in a style sometimes described as [[Mediterranean cuisine]].]]\nMartel attended [[Phillips Academy]] in [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]] and graduated in the school's first co&ndash;educational class in 1974. Her classmates included jazz Grammy&ndash;winner [[Bill Cunliffe]], software financier [[Peter Currie (businessman)|Peter Currie]], actor [[Dana Delany]], painter [[Julian Hatton]], poet [[Karl Kirchwey]], writer [[Nate Lee]], television producer [[Jonathan Meath]], editor [[Sara Nelson]], and sculptor [[Gar Waterman]]. She graduated from [[Brown University]] in 1978. Her love of writing was influenced in part after taking a course at [[Wesleyan University|Wesleyan]] called ''Portraits of People'' taught by Anne Greene, in the 1980s.<ref name=\"twsNHI\"/>\n\nMartel and van Over opened a [[Chester, Connecticut]] restaurant which they named ''Restaurant du Village'' in 1979 and sold it in 1990.<ref name=twsOctN32>{{cite news\n |author= LARY BLOOM\n |title= Lessons From the Founding Fireplaces \n |newspaper= The New York Times\n |quote= It\u2019s true that Mr. Van Over, at 70, has been much more widely known for his advice in the kitchen than other parts of the house. He served as a restaurant consultant even before he and his wife, Priscilla Martel, opened Restaurant du Village, which helped make Chester a destination. (They sold it in 1990). \n |date= February 10, 2008\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/10/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/10colct.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> In 2010, they own a firm called \"All About Food\" which holds baking patents and collaborates with food manufacturers and restaurants on such matters as menus, marketing programs, and new products.<ref name=twsOctN34/>\n\n[[File:Fireplace Burning.jpg|thumb|right|Martel and van Over have friends for dinner and often cook in a [[fireplace]] and outdoor wood&ndash;fired oven.]]\nMartel and van Over were quoted in the ''[[New York Times]]'' about doing [[rotisserie]] cooking using a [[fireplace]]; on occasions, Martel and van Over have cooked for fellow Chester resident and ''[[60 Minutes]]'' reporter [[Morley Safer]].<ref name=twsOctN23>{{cite news\n |author= ELIZABETH MAKER\n |title= CONNECTICUT AT ITS BEST; On an Open Fire, Much More Than Chestnuts\n |newspaper= The New York Times\n |quote= Charlie van Over of Chester,... wife, Priscilla Martel, throw in fall and winter for guests who include Morley Safer of ''60 Minutes'' and the chef Jacques P?n, both of whom live in Chester. '... the Broadway actor Peter Kapetan, ...\n |date= December 11, 2005\n |url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F05E0D61131F932A25751C1A9639C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> The couple would cook a multicourse meal in the fireplace while having sing&ndash;a&ndash;longs which sometimes included dancing, and their dinners often included [[quail]], duck, [[venison]] or [[porterhouse steak]].<ref name=twsOctN23/> At one point, Martel and van Over lived in a house with six<ref name=twsOctN32/> or seven fireplaces.<ref name=twsOctN23/> Martel said the fireplace cooking experiences \"brings out the best in people.\"<ref name=twsOctN23/> They grow vegetables and other foods in their garden for some of their meals.<ref name=twsOctN25/> The dining table often has beautiful flowers such as [[zinnia]]s and [[Antirrhinum|snapdragons]] and meals are often served with wine.<ref name=twsOctN25/> Martel and van Over advise restaurants about such matters as how to create a [[brasserie]].<ref name=twsOctN31>{{cite news\n |author= STEPHANIE LYNESS\n |title= A New Brasserie That Knows What It Is \n |newspaper= The New York Times\n |quote= ... (Mr. Van Over, a Connecticut  chef and the original owner, with his wife, Priscilla Martel, of Restaurant du Village in Chester, was a consultant on the creation of the brasserie.) \n |date= October 14, 2006\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/14/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/15ctdine.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> Beef steak and veal stew are cooked using a Tuscan grill.<ref name=twsOctN32/> Martel and van Over argued in their book \"The Best Bread Ever\" that the best way to make the perfect loaf is to use a [[food processor]].<ref name=twsOctN32/> Martel's recipes entitled ''Cod with creamy nut sauce'' and ''Chicken Almond Curry with Apricots'' appeared in ''[[Food & Wine]]'' magazine.<ref name=twsOctN15>{{cite news\n |author= Priscilla Martel\n |title= Recipe search\n |publisher= Food and Wine\n |date= October 20, 2010\n |url= http://www.foodandwine.com/search/recipe.cfm?title=&chef=Priscilla+Martel&ingredient=&type=Entree&recipe_ethnic=&holiday_occasion=&cooking_method=&servings=&seasons=&pub_month=&pub_year=&search_submit=Submit+Query&per=25\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref> She is co-author of culinary textbooks ''On Baking: A Textbook of Baking and Pastry Fundamentals'' and ''On Cooking: A Textbook of Culinary Fundamentals''.<ref name=\"twsNHReg\"/> She works as a consultant in product development to create international seafood chowders and Italian regional soups for [[Borden Milk Products|Borden]].<ref name=\"twsNHReg\"/> For [[Absolut Vodka]], she is a spokesperson and developer of recipes.<ref name=\"twsNHReg\"/> She wrote over 150 columns entitled ''All About Food'' in Connecticut newspapers.<ref name=\"twsNHI\">{{cite web \n| author= LUCY GELLMAN\n| date= January 26, 2016\n| publisher= New Haven Independent\n| url= http://www.newhavenindependent.org/index.php/archives/entry/food_writing_comes_to_gateway/\n| title= Food Writer Cooks Up A Gateway Course\n| accessdate= February 11, 2016\n| quote=...By the time Priscilla Martel took Anne Greene\u2019s \u201cPortraits of People,\u201d a creative nonfiction course taught at Wesleyan University in the 1980s...\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Almond and Mixed Berry Shortcakes by Priscilla Martel.jpg|thumb|right|Martel created the recipe for this dessert entitled \"Almond and Mixed Berry Shortcakes\". For recipe, see external links.]]\n\n==Publications==\n* ''On Baking: A Textbook of Baking and Pastry Fundamentals,'' by Sarah Labensky, Priscilla Martel and Eddy Vandamme {{ISBN|978-0-13-157923-1}}\n* ''Sampler Companion Website for On Baking: A Textbook of Baking and Pastry Fundamentals'' {{ISBN|978-0-13-504653-1}}<ref name=twsOctN11>{{cite news\n |author= Priscilla Martel\n |title= Sampler Companion Website for On Baking: A Textbook of Baking and Pastry Fundamentals\n |publisher= Pearson Higher Education\n |year= 2009\n |url= http://vig.pearsonhighered.com/educator/academic/product/0,3110,013504653X,00.html\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref>\n* ''On Cooking: A Textbook Of Culinary Fundamentals'', by Sarah Labensky, Alan M. Hause, Steven Labensky, Priscilla Martel; book/CD <ref name=twsOctN14>{{cite news\n |title= On cooking\n |publisher= otoku-money\n |quote= Mastercook cd for on cooking, 4/e; sarah r. labensky; alan m. hause, fabulous food; steven r. labensky; priscilla a. martel, the center for the culinary arts; ...\n |year= 2010\n |url= http://otoku-money.info/uvplm9/xnfpb.php?on-cooking-a-textbook-labensky\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref>\n* ''The Best Bread Ever: Great Homemade Bread Using Your Food Processor'' by Charles van Over and Priscilla Martel (1997)<ref name=twsOctN33>{{cite news\n |author= Charles van Over and Priscilla Martel (authors)\n |title= The Best Bread Ever\n |publisher= Bookstores.com\n |quote= The Best Bread Ever: Great Homemade Bread Using Your Food Processor (1st Edition)\n |year= 1997\n |url= http://www.allbookstores.com/Priscilla-Martel/author\n |accessdate= October 20, 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110709014938/http://www.dessertprofessional.com/profile/