{"title_page": "Eduardo V\u00e9lez (tennis)", "text_new": "{{short description|Mexican tennis player}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name = Eduardo V\u00e9lez\n| image =\n| fullname = Eduardo V\u00e9lez\n| country_represented = {{MEX}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|4|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Monterrey]], Mexico\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| plays = Right-handed\n| careerprizemoney = $27,065\n| singlesrecord = 3\u20135\n| singlestitles = 0\n| highestsinglesranking = No. 215 (30 November 1987)\n| currentsinglesranking = \n| AustralianOpenresult =\n| FrenchOpenresult = \n| Wimbledonresult =\n| USOpenresult =\n| doublesrecord = 0\u20131\n| doublestitles = 0\n| highestdoublesranking = No. 435 (21 November 1988)\n| currentdoublesranking = \n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult =\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult = \n| WimbledonDoublesresult =\n| USOpenDoublesresult =\n}}\n'''Eduardo V\u00e9lez''' (born 20 April 1969) is a former professional [[tennis]] player from Mexico.\n\n==Biography==\nV\u00e9lez, who comes from [[Monterrey]], attended [[Cardinal Gibbons High School (Fort Lauderdale, Florida)|Cardinal Gibbons High School]] in [[Fort Lauderdale]] and trained at the local tennis academy run by Gary Kesl.<ref name=\"Sarni\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1986-07-07/sports/8602100147_1_junior-title-seventh-singles-title-wimbledon-facts|title=King Of The Juniors Again Is From Kesl: It`s Gibbons` Velez|last=Sarni|first=Jim|date=7 July 1986|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> He won the [[Junior Orange Bowl (tennis)|Junior Orange Bowl]] (Under 14s) in 1983 and was the Mexican junior champion in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://juniororangebowl.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/160434-JOB-Tennis-Program-10.pdf|title=Junior Orange Bowl International Tennis Championship - Tennis Program|year=2014|publisher=[[Orange Bowl]]|page=15|accessdate=7 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126092739/http://juniororangebowl.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/160434-JOB-Tennis-Program-10.pdf|archive-date=26 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"ATP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/en/players/eduardo-velez/v096/bio|title=Eduardo Velez - Bio - ATP World Tour - Tennis|publisher=[[Association of Tennis Professionals]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> A [[Mexico Davis Cup team|Mexican Davis Cup]] squad member, he twice made the boys' singles final at the [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon Championships]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19870627&id=lcVUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZJADAAAAIBAJ&pg=5146,5591670&hl=en|title=Mexico lose Maciel|date=27 June 1987|work=[[New Straits Times]]|page=18|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/juniors/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=10001443|title=ITF Tennis - Juniors - Player Profile - Velez, Eduardo (MEX)|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> He defeated [[Javier S\u00e1nchez (tennis)|Javier S\u00e1nchez]] to win the [[1986 Wimbledon Championships]], the second successive time a Mexican won the title, as he was beaten in the final the previous year by countryman [[Leonardo Lavalle]].<ref name=\"Sarni\"/>\n\nAfter his success at Wimbledon, V\u00e9lez played in the main draw of two [[Grand Prix tennis circuit|Grand Prix]] tournaments, the [[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships]] in Boston and the [[Washington Open (tennis)|Washington DC Tennis Classic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/tournaments/men's-tournament/info.aspx?tournamentid=1010002098|title=ITF Tennis - Pro Circuit - Boston - 21 July - 27 July 1986|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/tournaments/men's-tournament/info.aspx?tournamentid=1010003456|title=ITF Tennis - Pro Circuit - Washington DC - 28 July - 03 August 1986\n|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> In 1987, he played in the main draw of the [[Bristol Open]]; then in 1988, he featured at the [[Livingston Open]], where he lost in the first round to [[Andre Agassi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/06/17/Tennis-ResultsNEWLN100000-Tournament-At-Bristol-England-June-17/6044550900800/|title=Tennis Results|date=June 17, 1987|publisher=[[United Press International]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/13805033/|title=Agassi Rolling|date=August 17, 1988|work=Logansport Pharos-Tribune|page=13|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> He also competed on the [[ATP Challenger Tour|Challenger]] circuit and in 1988 won a title in [[Acapulco]]. His 1989 season was ruined by injury, he had to undergo surgery on his knee cap and soon after hurt his back.<ref name=\"ATP\"/> In 1990, he qualified for the [[1990 Canadian Open (tennis)|Canadian Open]], a top tier event part of the [[1990 ATP Championship Series, Single Week|ATP Championship Series]].<ref name=\"Toronto\">{{cite news|url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/tournaments/men's-tournament/info.aspx?tournamentid=1010001217|title=ITF Tennis - Pro Circuit - Canadian Open - 23 July - 29 July 1990|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> He defeated [[Dan Goldie]] in the first round, before losing in the second round to ninth seed [[David Wheaton]].<ref name=\"Toronto\"/>\n\n==Challenger titles==\n===Singles: (1)===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=font-size:97%\n!width=50|No.\n!width=145|Year\n!width=200|Tournament\n!width=75|Surface\n!width=200|Opponent\n!width=200|Score\n|- \n|1.\n|1988\n|[[Acapulco]], Mexico\n|Hard\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Paul Chamberlin]] \n|7\u20136, 7\u20136\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ATP|v096}}\n* {{ITF male profile|10001443}}\n\n{{Wimbledon boys' singles champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Velez, Eduardo}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon junior champions]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Monterrey]]\n[[Category:Mexican expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in boys' singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mexican tennis player}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name = Eduardo V\u00e9lez\n| image =\n| fullname = Eduardo V\u00e9lez\n| country_represented = {{MEX}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|4|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Monterrey]], Mexico\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| plays = Right-handed\n| careerprizemoney = $27,065\n| singlesrecord = 3\u20135\n| singlestitles = 0\n| highestsinglesranking = No. 215 (30 November 1987)\n| currentsinglesranking = \n| AustralianOpenresult =\n| FrenchOpenresult = \n| Wimbledonresult =\n| USOpenresult =\n| doublesrecord = 0\u20131\n| doublestitles = 0\n| highestdoublesranking = No. 435 (21 November 1988)\n| currentdoublesranking = \n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult =\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult = \n| WimbledonDoublesresult =\n| USOpenDoublesresult =\n}}\n'''Eduardo V\u00e9lez''' (born 20 April 1969) is a former professional [[tennis]] player from Mexico.\n\n==Biography==\nV\u00e9lez, who comes from [[Monterrey]], attended [[Cardinal Gibbons High School (Fort Lauderdale, Florida)|Cardinal Gibbons High School]] in [[Fort Lauderdale]] and trained at the local tennis academy run by Gary Kesl.<ref name=\"Sarni\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1986-07-07/sports/8602100147_1_junior-title-seventh-singles-title-wimbledon-facts|title=King Of The Juniors Again Is From Kesl: It`s Gibbons` Velez|last=Sarni|first=Jim|date=7 July 1986|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> He won the [[Junior Orange Bowl (tennis)|Junior Orange Bowl]] (Under 14s) in 1983 and was the Mexican junior champion in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://juniororangebowl.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/160434-JOB-Tennis-Program-10.pdf|title=Junior Orange Bowl International Tennis Championship - Tennis Program|year=2014|publisher=[[Orange Bowl]]|page=15|accessdate=7 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126092739/http://juniororangebowl.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/160434-JOB-Tennis-Program-10.pdf|archive-date=26 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"ATP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/en/players/eduardo-velez/v096/bio|title=Eduardo Velez - Bio - ATP World Tour - Tennis|publisher=[[Association of Tennis Professionals]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> A [[Mexico Davis Cup team|Mexican Davis Cup]] squad member, he twice made the boys' singles final at the [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon Championships]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19870627&id=lcVUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZJADAAAAIBAJ&pg=5146,5591670&hl=en|title=Mexico lose Maciel|date=27 June 1987|work=[[New Straits Times]]|page=18|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/juniors/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=10001443|title=ITF Tennis - Juniors - Player Profile - Velez, Eduardo (MEX)|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> He defeated [[Javier S\u00e1nchez]] to win the [[1986 Wimbledon Championships]], the second successive time a Mexican won the title, as he was beaten in the final the previous year by countryman [[Leonardo Lavalle]].<ref name=\"Sarni\"/>\n\nAfter his success at Wimbledon, V\u00e9lez played in the main draw of two [[Grand Prix tennis circuit|Grand Prix]] tournaments, the [[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships]] in Boston and the [[Washington Open (tennis)|Washington DC Tennis Classic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/tournaments/men's-tournament/info.aspx?tournamentid=1010002098|title=ITF Tennis - Pro Circuit - Boston - 21 July - 27 July 1986|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/tournaments/men's-tournament/info.aspx?tournamentid=1010003456|title=ITF Tennis - Pro Circuit - Washington DC - 28 July - 03 August 1986\n|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> In 1987, he played in the main draw of the [[Bristol Open]]; then in 1988, he featured at the [[Livingston Open]], where he lost in the first round to [[Andre Agassi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/06/17/Tennis-ResultsNEWLN100000-Tournament-At-Bristol-England-June-17/6044550900800/|title=Tennis Results|date=June 17, 1987|publisher=[[United Press International]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/13805033/|title=Agassi Rolling|date=August 17, 1988|work=Logansport Pharos-Tribune|page=13|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> He also competed on the [[ATP Challenger Tour|Challenger]] circuit and in 1988 won a title in [[Acapulco]]. His 1989 season was ruined by injury, he had to undergo surgery on his knee cap and soon after hurt his back.<ref name=\"ATP\"/> In 1990, he qualified for the [[1990 Canadian Open (tennis)|Canadian Open]], a top tier event part of the [[1990 ATP Championship Series, Single Week|ATP Championship Series]].<ref name=\"Toronto\">{{cite news|url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/tournaments/men's-tournament/info.aspx?tournamentid=1010001217|title=ITF Tennis - Pro Circuit - Canadian Open - 23 July - 29 July 1990|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> He defeated [[Dan Goldie]] in the first round, before losing in the second round to ninth seed [[David Wheaton]].<ref name=\"Toronto\"/>\n\n==Challenger titles==\n===Singles: (1)===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=font-size:97%\n!width=50|No.\n!width=145|Year\n!width=200|Tournament\n!width=75|Surface\n!width=200|Opponent\n!width=200|Score\n|- \n|1.\n|1988\n|[[Acapulco]], Mexico\n|Hard\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Paul Chamberlin]] \n|7\u20136, 7\u20136\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ATP|v096}}\n* {{ITF male profile|10001443}}\n\n{{Wimbledon boys' singles champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Velez, Eduardo}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon junior champions]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Monterrey]]\n[[Category:Mexican expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in boys' singles]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJavier S\u00e1nchez(link changed toJavier S\u00e1nchez (tennis)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eduardo_V%C3%A9lez_(tennis)"}
{"title_page": "Karl Kirchwey", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Karl Kirchwey\n| image = File:T.S. Eliot and the Mind of Europe - 25841267534 (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Kirchwey speaks at a Boston University event in 2016\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1956|02|25}}\n| birth_place = \n| nationality = American\n| occupation = Poet,<br/> translator,<br/> teacher,<br/> literary curator\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| residence = Boston, Massachusetts\n| alma_mater = [[Yale College|Yale]] [[bachelor of arts]] 1979<br/>[[master of arts]] from [[Columbia University|Columbia]]<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n| notable_works= ''The Engrafted Word''<br/>1998<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n| influenced  = \n| website = \n| signature = \n| parents =\n}}\n\n'''Karl Kirchwey''' (born February 25, 1956) is an award\u2013winning<ref name=twsOctBg677/> American poet who has lived in both Europe and the United States and whose work is strongly influenced by the [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] and [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] past. He often looks to the [[classical world]] for inspiration, with themes which have included loss, loneliness, nostalgia, and modern atrocities, and how the past relates to the present.<ref name=twsOctByree/><ref name=twsOctBxfsf/> While he is best known for his poems, he also is a [[book reviewer]],<ref name=twsOctB34er>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= Derek Walcott, Man of Many Voices \n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= More than almost any other contemporary poet, Derek Walcott might seem to be fulfilling T. S. Eliot's program for poetry. He has distinguished himself in all of what Eliot described as the \"three voices of poetry\": the lyric, the narrative or epic, and the dramatic. \n |date= April 22, 2010\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/books/review/Kirchwey-t.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctB8io>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= Poetry's Shadow\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= But whereas Lawrence is discursively tender, and Rexroth wry and epigrammatically clever, Jeffrey Yang speaks in tongues as if touched with a Pentecostal flame. He leads the reader through a net of allusions in poems barnacled with hard words. \n |date= December 19, 2008 \n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/21/books/review/Kirchwey-t.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> award-winning teacher of creative writing,<ref name=twsOctBvbcv>{{cite news\n |title= Creative Writing Program Director Karl Kirchwey to Serve as Andrew Heiskell Arts Director at the American Academy in Rome\n |publisher= Bryn Mawr\n |quote= In 2003 Kirchwey received Bryn Mawr's Rosalyn R. Schwartz Teaching Award.\n |date= April 27, 2010\n |url= http://news.brynmawr.edu/?p=5525\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> translator, arts administrator,<ref name=twsOctB75544/> [[curator|literary curator]], and advocate for writers and writing. He was director of the Unterberg Poetry Center of the [[92nd Street Y]] for 13 years,<ref name=twsOctB75544/> directed and taught in the Creative Writing Program at Bryn Mawr College from 2000 to 2010,<ref name=twsOctBeqqq/> served as [[Andrew Heiskell]] Arts Director at the [[American Academy in Rome]] from 2010 to 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aarome.org/#rt=news&rid=162|title=American Academy in Rome &#124; American Academy in Rome|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref> and is currently professor and director of the MFA Program in creative writing at [[Boston University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bu.edu/creativewriting/karl-kirchwey/|title=Karl Kirchwey \u00bb Writing \u00bb Boston University|website=www.bu.edu|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===College years===\n[[File:Phillips Academy, Andover, MA - Samuel Phillips Hall.JPG|thumb|right|Kirchwey attended Phillips Academy in Andover.]]\nKirchwey was born in 1956 and graduated from [[Phillips Academy]] in [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]] in 1974 in the boarding school's first co-educational class, which included jazz musician [[Bill Cunliffe]], software executive [[Peter Currie (businessman)|Peter Currie]], actor [[Dana Delany]], painter [[Julian Hatton]], writer [[Nate Lee]], political commentator [[Heather Mac Donald]], restaurateur [[Priscilla Martel]], TV producer [[Jonathan Meath]], editor [[Sara Nelson (editor)|Sara Nelson]], and sculptor [[Gar Waterman]]. He attended [[Yale College|Yale]], but described his first two undergraduate years as \"unfocused and unproductive.\"<ref name=twsOctBeqqq>{{cite news\n |author= John swansburg\n |title= At Yale, Lessons in Writing and in Life\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= Karl Kirchwey, who graduated from Yale in 1979, recently became the director of creative writing at Bryn Mawr College, after having run the Unterberg Poetry Center at the 92nd Street Y for over a decade. He remembers his first two years at Yale as unfocused and unproductive.\n |date= April 29, 2001\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/29/nyregion/at-yale-lessons-in-writing-and-in-life.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> He took a class on [[Metre (poetry)|versification]] taught by Penelope Laurans, which gave him the sense that he had an \"ear for verse\", but his work was \"less than diligent\" in his own estimation.<ref name=twsOctBeqqq/> He took a year off and worked at Cutler's Record Shop in [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]]. After his year off, he studied with poet [[John Hollander]] and discovered that building a life around the task of writing poetry was possible. Kirchwey described Hollander as a master of both [[British poetry|English]] and [[American poetry]] and said:\n\n{{cquote|Since he (John Hollander) is a poet himself ... he conveyed a passion for that knowledge as a source of current inspiration.<br/>--Karl Kirchwey in 2001<ref name=twsOctBeqqq/>}}\n\nHollander taught him that poems were more than mere creations, but have an inspirational force, and gave Kirchwey greater respect for intellectual and artistic pursuits, as well as for Yale.\n\n{{cquote|Why was Yale unique? At that point it wasn't because there was a creative writing program there, because there wasn't (and still isn't). Instead, it had to do with a sense that creative writing, that poetry in my case, was arising out of this superb intellectual climate where art was taken seriously.<br/>--Karl Kirchwey in 2001<ref name=twsOctBeqqq/>}}\n\nKirchwey graduated with a [[bachelor of arts]] degree in [[English literature]] from Yale and with an master of arts in [[English literature]] from [[Columbia University|Columbia]].<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n\n===Teaching===\nBetween 1979 and 1984, Kirchwey taught English literature and composition at the Andover Summer Session. He also taught at the [[The American School In Switzerland|American School in Switzerland]] in [[Lugano, Switzerland|Lugano]], and at Elisabeth Irwin High School in New York City.\n\n[[File:Aeneas Creusa Louvre OA7554.jpg|thumb|right|In Vergil's ''Aeneid'', the hero Aeneas sees a vision of his dead wife [[Creusa]], who tries to relieve Aeneas from grieving by telling him that her death had been fated.]]\nFrom 1995 to 1997, Kirchwey drove weekly between New York City and western Massachusetts, where he taught writing at [[Smith College]]. During these drives, he would listen to tapes of [[epic poetry]], including a translation of [[Vergil]] by [[Robert Fitzgerald]]. During one drive, Kirchwey felt lost in the entangled ramps of what his grandmother had once termed the \"Hartford spaghetti\" stretch of Interstate 91; he described it as \"bewildering, tortuous, and layered are the whorls of its entrance and exit ramps\".<ref name=twsOctBv122/> Kirchwey wrote later how that driving experience had reminded him of Vergil's hero Aeneas, who after having fled [[Troy]] during its nighttime destruction by the Greek army, returned to the burning city to search for his missing wife Creusa, but who became lost temporarily.<ref name=twsOctBv122/> Creusa's ghost appears to Aeneas to tell him that her death had been fated and that he can do nothing about it and that he must continue with his life.<ref name=twsOctBv122/> Kirchwey wrote how his experience in Hartford was similar to that of Aeneas in Troy:\n\n{{cquote|And I felt this huge weariness of the hero as he was told, with a [[wisdom]] surpassing human understanding, that he would build his life over again and found a new race in a new land ... This prophecy, the inexorability of the exchange of what one loves best for what [[Destiny|fate]] will have one do, seemed so authentically to mix bitterness and rapture, my own vision blurred for a while as the lights came on outside [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]] and I continued home. <br/>-- Karl Kirchwey, writing in ''Poets and critics read Vergil'' edited by Sarah Spence.<ref name=twsOctBv122>{{cite news\n |author= Sarah Spence (editor)\n |title= Poets and Critics Read Vergil\n |publisher= Yale University\n |quote= see pages 184\u2013185\n |year= 2001\n |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=tyZtZ95UHvsC&pg=PA184 \n |isbn=0-300-08376-9\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref>}}\n\nKirchwey taught at Smith College, Yale, [[Wesleyan University|Wesleyan]], and in the master of fine arts program at Columbia.<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/> He taught at Bryn Mawr from 2000 to 2014, where he was professor of the arts and director of creative writing.<ref name=twsOctBeqqq/> From 2010 to 2013, he took leave from Bryn Mawr to serve as [[Andrew Heiskell]] Arts Director at the [[American Academy in Rome]].<ref name=twsOctBcsdde>{{cite web\n |title= Karl Kirchwey\n |publisher= Boston University\n |quote= Karl Kirchwey is the author of six books of poems: A Wandering Island (Princeton University Press, 1990; recipient of the Norma Farber First Book Award from the Poetry Society of America), Those I Guard (Harcourt Brace and Company, 1993), The Engrafted Word (Henry Holt, 1998; a New York Times \u201cNotable Book of the Year\u201d), and At the Palace of Jove (2002), The Happiness of This World: Poetry and Prose (2007) and Mount Lebanon (2011), all published by Marian Wood Books/Putnam\u2019s.\n |date= June 15, 2014\n |url= http://www.bu.edu/creativewriting/karl-kirchwey/\n |accessdate= 28 July 2014\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctBzxcxx>{{cite news\n |author= Karen Heller\n |title= Bryn Mawr shows creative side as it makes way for arts\n |work= Chicago Tribune\n |quote= And that's fine by Karl Kirchwey. \"My job is to put Bryn Mawr on the map for literature, and as a place to study creative writing,\" says the long, lanky, passionate poet in command of an astonishing Rolodex. The author of four books of poetry, many inspired by classical literature, and a graduate of Yale and Columbia, Kirchwey has been awarded Guggenheim, National Endowment for the Arts and Ingram Merrill fellowships, as well as the vaunted Rome Prize in Literature. In the three years since the 47-year-old poet left the famed Unterberg Poetry Center at New York's 92nd Street Y, Kirchwey has quietly, but quickly, increased attention to the written word on the sylvan, suburban campus.\n |date= May 1, 2003\n |url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-05-01/features/0305010107_1_bryn-mawr-college-marianne-moore-samson-agonistes\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> At Bryn Mawr he taught creative writing courses in poetry and memoir and literature courses in [[classical mythology|Classical Myth]] and its contemporary updates, [[modernist poetry]], and [[American poetry#Modernism and after|contemporary American poetry]].<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/> He received Bryn Mawr's Rosalyn R. Schwartz Teaching Award in 2003.<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/>\n\n[[File:Entrance Bryn Mawr.JPG|thumb|right|Bryn Mawr College is located in a suburb near Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.]]\nAccording to one account, Bryn Mawr in the 1990s began a project to raise the national stature of its writing program, as well as \"its profile in the arts\" according to provost Ralph Kuncl, and Kirchwey was hired in 2000 as part of this effort.<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/> College president [[Nancy J. Vickers|Nancy Vickers]] applauded Kirchwey's efforts to bring talented writers to lecture on the campus.<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/> Kirchwey said:\n\n{{cquote|My job is to put Bryn Mawr on the map for literature, and as a place to study creative writing.<br/> \u2013 Karl Kirchwey in 2003.<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/>}}\n\nKirchwey helped bring numerous writers to campus including [[Nobel laureate]]s [[Derek Walcott]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> [[Nadine Gordimer]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> and [[Nigeria]]'s [[Wole Soyinka]], as well as writers such as [[Peter Cameron (writer)|Peter Cameron]], [[Sandra Cisneros]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> novelist [[E. L. Doctorow]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> [[Umberto Eco]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> [[Jessica Hagedorn]], [[Maxine Hong Kingston]], [[James Lasdun]],<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/> [[Peter Matthiessen]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> novelist [[Ian McEwan]], [[Sigrid Nunez]], [[Susan-Lori Parks]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> [[Robert Pinsky]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> [[Zadie Smith]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> [[Mark Strand]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> playwright [[August Wilson]], and others. Actors [[Claire Bloom]] and [[John Neville (actor)|John Neville]] did a stage reading of [[John Milton|Milton's]] ''[[Samson Agonistes]]''.<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/> A Bryn Mawr publication described Kirchwey's efforts as successful, and wrote that he diversified and expanded the creative writing program to make it a \"premier stop\" for writers in the Philadelphia region.<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/>\n\nIn 2010, Kirchwey was named the Andrew Heiskell Arts Director at the American Academy in Rome, which is an independent privately funded institution that encourages scholarly and artistic projects associated with the culture of Rome.<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> Its mission is \"to foster the pursuit of advanced research and independent study in the fine arts and humanities,\" according to a statement on its website.<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx11>{{cite web\n |title= Mission statement\n |publisher= American Academy in Rome\n |quote= The mission of the American Academy in Rome, founded in 1894, is to foster the pursuit of advanced research and independent study in the fine arts and humanities.\n |date= October 18, 2010\n |url= http://www.aarome.org/\n |accessdate= 18 October 2010\n}}</ref> Kirchwey returned to Bryn Mawr for the 2013\u201314 academic year.<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> A Bryn Mawr publication described Kirchwey's role in Italy as \"shaping and articulating the Academy's broad vision for the arts\" in terms of guiding programs.<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> Beginning in September 2014 he will be Professor and Director of the MFA Program in Creative Writing at [[Boston University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.bu.edu/crwr/2014/07/11/welcome-karl-kirchwey-literary-links/|title=Welcome, Karl Kirchwey! + literary links &#124; BU Creative Writing|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nKirchwey has written poetry consistently during his career, and by 2011 had published six books of poetry in addition to a translation of Paul Verlaine's first book of poems as ''Poems Under Saturn''. He was influenced by the civilizations of classical Ancient Rome and Ancient Greece and has a European orientation in some of his poems, as well as a [[religion|religious sensibility]].<ref name=twsOctBbdss/> For example, his poem entitled \"Mutabor\" meaning ''change'' had references to the [[Hindu]] god [[Parvati]] and [[Shiva]] and a section of the poem, which appeared in the online publication ''[[Poetry (magazine)|Poetry Daily]]'', described a boy and a girl in a gorge.<ref name=twsOctBbdss>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= Mutabor: The Gorge\n |work= Poetry Daily\n |quote= They went down to the gorge of the Petite Gryonne ... in May, this was, a boy and a girl ... a hollow melted in it like the cave where immortal Parvati ... rubbed her own skin to make the jovial god... (from Mutabor: The Gorge by Karl Kirchwey)\n |date= November 2009\n |url= http://poems.com/poem.php?date=14566\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> Kirchwey based the poem on his memory as a youth of a cold stream called the Petite Gyronne near a bridge that ran in a secret gorge between the village of Chesi\u00e8res and the ski resort of Villars in the [[Alps Mountains]] in the French-speaking part of [[Switzerland]].<ref name=twsOctBbdss/> He wrote that a place near the gorge was where it had been said that \"the bravest of the boys would walk the entire length of the narrow bridge-railing, a hundred feet or more above the stream bed, even (once) blindfolded.\"<ref name=twsOctBbdss/> In Kirchwey's poem, the boy and the girl are lovers in a hollow near a heap of melting snow in May who \"faced with the water's endlessness\" and the \"untranslatable grief of the bird's paraphrase\" became wise in their lovemaking: \"they were never wiser than in that knowledge,\" he wrote in the poem.<ref name=twsOctBbdss/> In addition, events in his life, such as the death of his mother, have influenced his poetry.<ref name=twsOctB2111>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= The Red Portrait\n |publisher= Poetry Foundation\n |quote= Last night she came to me, my mother, dead: but as she was in the photo, that last Christmas ... ...  I told her how her life had informed mine, and I begged her to come to me again ... ... But she smiled at me and began to fade. \u2013 Karl Kirchwey\n |date= March 2008\n |url= http://www.poetryfoundation.org/archive/poem.html?id=181178\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref>\n\nKirchwey spent from September 1994 to July 1995 at the Academy in Rome as part of the Rome Prize, and described the experience as having \"completely shaped\" his third book of poems.<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/>\n\nIn 1998, Kirchwey's ''The Engrafted Word'' was published by Holt in hardcover and paperback versions.<ref name=twsOctB5999>{{cite news\n |author= Libby Larsen\n |title= Customer reviews\n |publisher= Amazon.com\n |quote= Kirchwey does an amazing job of synthesizing ideas from a number of spheres- such as obstetrics, physics, superstition, mythology, biology, religion, chemistry, Roman history and poetry. Kirchwey accomplishes said task by engrafting technical words upon each other, words that outwardly have little in common. Moreover, Kirchwey's great use of setting enables me to feel the location of each poem. \n |date= April 10, 2000\n |url= https://www.amazon.com/Engrafted-Word-Poems-Karl-Kirchwey/product-reviews/0805056076/ref=dp_top_cm_cr_acr_txt?ie=UTF8&showViewpoints=1\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> It revealed Kirchwey's wide inquiry into disparate areas including [[obstetrics]], [[physics]], [[superstition]], [[mythology]], [[biology]], religion, [[chemistry]], and [[Roman history]].<ref name=twsOctB5999/> He ''engrafted'' technical words upon each other, sometimes words which seemed initially to have little in common with each other, and magically ''engrafts'' the \"past with the present\", according to one reviewer.<ref name=twsOctB5999/>\n\nIn 2002, ''At the Palace of Jove: Poems'' was published by Marian Wood Books/Putnam's. The book had classical references and was described by ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' as an exploration of how the past impacts the present.<ref name=twsOctByree>\n{{cite news\n |title= Nature & Environment\n |work= Publishers Weekly\n |quote= At the Palace of Jove (Oct., $26; paper $15) by Karl Kirchwey. Verse explores the impact of the past on the present.\n |date= August 12, 2002\n |url= http://reg.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/20020812/31096-fall-2002-hardcovers-nature-amp-environment-to-reference-.html?refresh\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110715131538/http://reg.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/20020812/31096-fall-2002-hardcovers-nature-amp-environment-to-reference-.html?refresh\n |archive-date= July 15, 2011\n |url-status= dead\n |df= mdy-all\n }}\n</ref> The magazine felt that Kirchwey's poems entitled ''Elegies'' weren't strictly about [[mourning]] but rather were \"quiet inquiries into what the mind does to compensate for spiritual silence.\"<ref name=twsOctByree/>\n\nIn 2007, Kirchwey published ''The Happiness of this World'', which included poems such as \"Reading Akhmatova\" in which a child's [[speech therapy]] is contrasted with a Russian poet's experience and in which Kirchwey wrote phrases such as the \"widening diction of experience\".<ref name=twsOctB>{{cite news\n |author= Carl Rosin\n |title= Customer Reviews\n |publisher= Amazon.com\n |quote= I am especially fond of \"Reading Akhmatova\", in which a child's speech therapy runs through a book of the Russian poet's far-from-childish words and themes. We adults hear things in Akhmatova \u2013 this poem has a literariness that seems typical of Kirchwey's work \u2013 that clangs against the child's innocent enunciation of the words. The \"widening diction of experience\" evoked here is one of those rare lines (in modern poetry) with staying power for me \u2013 it has resonated with me for weeks.\n |date= February 23, 2008\n |url= https://www.amazon.com/Happiness-this-World-Karl-Kirchwey/product-reviews/0399153659/ref=dp_top_cm_cr_acr_txt?ie=UTF8&showViewpoints=1\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> The book included a prose memoir entitled \"A Yatra for Yama\", which described a journey Kirchwey made through Asia related to a family story in which a namesake uncle died in a [[World War II]] plane crash during the battle for [[Saipan]].<ref name=twsOctB/> A ''yatra'' is a journey.<ref name=twsOctB/>\n\nKirchwey's poems have appeared in ''[[AGNI (magazine)|AGNI]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bu.edu/agni/authors/K/Karl-Kirchwey.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 27, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226215301/http://www.bu.edu/agni/authors/K/Karl-Kirchwey.html |archive-date=December 26, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[The Atlantic]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[Grand Street (magazine)|Grand Street]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The Hudson Review]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The Kenyon Review]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The Nation]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thenation.com/doc/20041115/kirchwey |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 27, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007062346/http://www.thenation.com/doc/20041115/kirchwey |archive-date=October 7, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[The New Criterion]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The New Republic]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[Salmagundi]]'', ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nybooks.com/authors/130|title=Karl Kirchwey|website=The New York Review of Books|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/bios/karl_kirchwey/search?contributorName=karl%20kirchwey |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 27, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607062638/http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/bios/karl_kirchwey/search?contributorName=karl%20kirchwey |archive-date=June 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Parnassus (magazine)|Parnassus]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[Partisan Review]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[Poetry (magazine)|Poetry]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The Southwest Review]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The American Scholar (magazine)|American Scholar]]'', [[Sewanee Review]]'', ''[[Arion (journal)|Arion]]'', ''[[Tin House]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The Yale Review]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> and elsewhere.\n\nWhile known best for his poetry, Kirchwey also wrote the play ''Airdales & Cipher'', which was presented as a public reading at several venues, including the Appalachian Summer Festival in [[Boone, North Carolina]], as well as the 92nd Street Y.<ref name=twsOctBg677>\n{{cite news\n |title= Karl Kirchwey: Associate Professor and Director of Creative Writing\n |publisher= Bryn Mawr\n |quote= His play in verse entitled Airedales & Cipher, based on the Alcestis of Euripides, received the 1997 Paris Review Prize for Poetic Drama\n |year= 2010\n |url= http://www.brynmawr.edu/english/Faculty_and_Staff/smKirchwey.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20101008161358/http://www.brynmawr.edu/english/Faculty_and_Staff/smKirchwey.html\n |archive-date= October 8, 2010\n |url-status= dead\n |df= mdy-all\n }}\n</ref> The play was based on a work by Greek playwright [[Euripides]] entitled ''Alcestis'' and won the ''[[The Paris Review|Paris Review Prize]]'' in 1997 in the category of poetic drama.<ref name=twsOctBg677/> He has also read aloud the works of other writers such as [[Eudora Welty]].<ref name=twsOctB4ee3>\n{{cite news\n |author= Bob Summer\n |title= Volume 245 Issue\n |work= Publishers Weekly\n |quote= Notable, too, was the unusually large audience drawn to New York City's 92nd St. Y for the Library's launch event, an evening of readings of the honoree's stories by Ann Beattie, Ford, Randall Kenan, Karl Kirchwey (substituting for William Maxwell),\n |date= April 12, 1999\n |url= http://reg.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/19990412/40153-adoring-eudora-.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110715131627/http://reg.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/19990412/40153-adoring-eudora-.html\n |archive-date= July 15, 2011\n |url-status= dead\n |df= mdy-all\n }}\n</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Kirchwey published a sixth volume of poems entitled ''Mount Lebanon'', his third book with [[G. P. Putnam's Sons|Marian Wood Books\u2013Putnam's]].<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> ''[[Publishers Weekly]] wrote, \"Kirchwey seamlessly melds the contemporary and commonplace with the past and mythical,\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Karl Kirchwey. Putnam, $30 (112p) ISBN 978-0-399-15727-1 |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-399-15727-1 |title=Fiction Book Review: Mount Lebanon by Karl Kirchwey. Putnam, $30 (112p) ISBN 978-0-399-15727-1 |publisher=Publishersweekly.com |date=2011-03-21 |accessdate=2020-01-30}}</ref> and in ''[[Booklist]]'', Ray Olson remarked, \"Highly literate, Kirchwey uses his knowledge of religion, art, and history to inform his experience of the world....Expertly crafted throughout, this book attests a consummately cultured, thoroughly contemporary poet.\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vufind.uhls.org/vufind/Record/860312/Reviews |title=Archived copy |access-date=July 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140805081323/http://vufind.uhls.org/vufind/Record/860312/Reviews |archive-date=August 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Also in 2011, [[Princeton University Press]] published Kirchwey's translation of French poet [[Paul Verlaine]]'s first book as ''Poems Under Saturn''. Kirchwey's seventh book of poems, revisiting some of the sites of his third book ''The Engrafted Word'' and entitled ''Stumbling Blocks: Roman Poems'' is forthcoming.\n\n[[File:92Y jeh.jpg|thumb|right|The 92nd Street Y in New York City]]\n\n===92nd Street Y===\nIn 1984, Kirchwey joined the Poetry Center as assistant to the director of the Unterberg Poetry Center of the [[92nd Street Y]] in New York City, and became director in 1987, and he held this post until 2000.<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/><ref name=twsOctBeqqq/><ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/><ref name=twsOctBe2q3>{{cite news\n |title= Director Named at 92nd Street Y\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= Frederick Noonan, director of the Y's musical programs, and Karl Kirchwey, director of the poetry center, are to continue to direct their departments.\n |date= March 25, 2000\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/25/arts/director-named-at-92nd-street-y.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctB6yu>{{cite news\n |author= Glenn collins\n |title= When the Writers Read, the Readers Listen\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= ''There is a certain volatility about putting an audience together with a writer,'' said Karl Kirchwey, director of the Poetry Center of the 92d Street Y. ''Some authors look out at an audience and spontaneously decide not to read what they were going to. I really believe that in going to readings, people are reacting against the pre-packaged video and radio that is their normal fare and choosing a kind of live and unrehearsed spontaneity.'' (page 2)\n |date= October 23, 1989\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1989/10/23/books/when-the-writers-read-the-readers-listen.html?pagewanted=2\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> He [[curator|curated]] the Poetry Center's annual reading series, which included writers in all genres such as poetry, fiction, nonfiction, and drama.<ref name=twsOctB75544/> He staffed and taught a creative writing program for nonmatriculating adults. He also curated a series of lectures by literary biographers called \" Biographers and Brunch\" .<ref name=twsOctB75544/> He instituted programs that explored connections between literature and other art forms such as music and [[visual arts]].<ref name=twsOctB75544/> He was described as focusing on [[verse drama]] and presented plays by Nobel laureates [[Seamus Heaney]] and [[Derek Walcott]], as well as ones by [[Rita Dove]].<ref name=twsOctB75544/> In addition,  programs for high school students from New York City were presented.<ref name=twsOctB75544/> The center won grants from the Lila Wallace\u2013Reader's Digest Fund which helped make possible a national stage tour of Robert Pinsky's translation of Dante's ''[[Dante's Inferno|Inferno]]''.<ref name=twsOctB75544/> There was a thirteen-part radio series entitled ''The Poet's Voice'' broadcast on WNYC radio and later on ''[[National Public Radio]]''.<ref name=twsOctB75544/> The annual budget for the poetry center grew by a quarter of a million dollars, according to an account from the 92nd Street Y.<ref name=twsOctB75544/>\n\nAs director, Kirchwey encouraged New Yorkers to experience live readings by authors, since the format permits a \"certain volatility\" and spontaneity, in his view; readers benefit from hearing the author speak aloud, in person, and do not hear the usual \"prepackaged video and radio.\"<ref name=twsOctB6yu/> Kirchwey said that in some situations, authors who had been prepared to read a certain passage had changed their minds at the last instant upon seeing an audience, and read something else; in this sense, the medium is more dynamic than broadcast media such as television or radio.<ref name=twsOctB6yu/> Kirchwey commented in 1998 that he thought that more people were attending live readings, and that audiences were getting younger on average.<ref name=twsOctB6yu/> Kirchwey introduced writers such as [[Alice Walker]].<ref name=twsOctBjlop>{{cite news\n |title= Introduction by Karl Kirchwey \n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= On Tuesday, October 13, The New York Times and the 92nd Street Y presented a live broadcast of Alice Walker reading from her new novel, \"By the Light of My Father's Smile\". \n |year= 1998\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/10/04/specials/walker.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> Kirchwey has read his own poems on occasion.<ref name=twsOctBpyrt>{{cite news\n |title= Arts Briefing\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= The event tonight is a concert reading of Milton's verse play ''Samson Agonistes,'' directed by Robert Scanlan and starring Claire Bloom, John Neville, Jack Willis and Alvin Epstein, as well as the poets John Hollander, Karl Kirchwey and Rosanna Warren. (p.3)\n |date= April 21, 2003\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2003/04/21/movies/arts-briefing.html?pagewanted=3\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctBr654>{{cite news\n |title= SPARE TIMES: Feb. 9 \u2013 Feb. 15\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= Monday at 8:15&nbsp;pm, Karl Kirchwey, Grace Schulman and David Yezzi will read from their poems and prose;\n |date= February 9, 2007\n |url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E04E7D9113FF93AA35751C0A9619C8B63\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> Kirchwey attended events such as one honoring poet [[Stanley Kunitz]].<ref name=twsOctB0o9o>{{cite news\n |author= Gary shapiro \n |title= 'Leaves of Grass' at 150, Kunitz at (Almost) 100\n |publisher= The New York Sun\n |quote= STANLEY'S CENTENNIAL Poet Stanley Kunitz's 100th birthday is on July 29. But friends, family, and admirers filled the Tribeca Performing Arts Center to celebrate early. Last month Karl Kirchwey, Marie Howe, Lucie Brock-Broido, Gerald Stern, and others paid tribute to Mr. Kunitz before an audience filled with poets,\n |date= June 2, 2005\n |url= http://www.nysun.com/arts/leaves-of-grass-at-150-kunitz-at-almost-100/14801/\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> Kirchwey formally left the post of director of the 92nd Street Y in June 2000.<ref name=twsOctB75544>{{cite news\n |author=Alix Friedman \n |title=POETRY CENTER DIRECTOR KARL KIRCHWEY LEAVES 92nd STREET Y \n |publisher=92nd Street Y \n |quote=The 92nd Street Y announces the departure of Karl Kirchwey, longtime director of the 92nd Street Y Unterberg Poetry Center. Mr. Kirchwey will become Director of Creative Writing and Senior Lecturer in the Arts at Bryn Mawr College starting next fall. The Poetry Center is a program of the 92nd Street Y Tisch Center for the Arts, the Y's arts presenting division. \n |date=June 13, 2000 \n |url=http://www.92y.org/content/karl_kirchwey_leaves_poetry_center.asp\n |accessdate=15 October 2010 \n}}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Upon his departure in 2000, executive director Sol Adler said:\n\n{{cquote|It is with deep gratitude tinged with wistfulness that I accept Karl's resignation. He has done a great deal to honor and reflect upon the rich tradition of the Poetry Center, just as he has continued to attract new individual talents to our stage. We will miss him and wish him the very best. \u2013 Sol Adler in 2000.<ref name=twsOctB75544/>}}\n\n===Reviews of Kirchwey's poetry===\nA review of ''The Engrafted Word'' by writer [[Mary Jo Salter]] in ''[[The New York Times]]'' suggested Kirchwey's book of poems was ''transformative'' and ''elegant''.<ref name=twsOctBxfsf>{{cite news\n |author= Mary jo salter\n |title= Transfigurations: Karl Kirchwey believes that the poetic word can save our souls. \n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= Those readers familiar with Kirchwey's earlier work know him as a poet for whom the world of antiquity is as real as this morning's breakfast. The aural transformation from ''sinuses'' to ''Siracusa's'' comes from deep within the maker's sensibility. \n |date= August 9, 1998\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/08/09/reviews/980809.09saltert.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> Salter applauded Kirchwey's \"sensual accuracies\" in such poems by commenting on one of Kirchwey's poetic lines. Salter writes: \"A [[Medical ultrasonography|sonogram]]\u2014that routine magic whereby a mother's womb turns into a crystal ball\u2014opens Karl Kirchwey's elegant third collection of poems.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/08/09/reviews/980809.09saltert.html| work=The New York Times| date=August 9, 1998| title=Transfigurations \u2013 Karl Kirchwey |author=Mary Jo Salter}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|Something of desk work and pornography\nthrough succulences of conducting gel.<br/>--Karl Kirchwey in ''The Engrafted Word''<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/>}}\n\nSalter suggested that the repeated syllables with the ''uck'' sound evoked the sound of the experience of a sonogram, including the discomfort.<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/> She described Kirchwey's poetry as being \"steeped in allusions to [[classical mythology]], history, literature.<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/> For example, she notes how Kirchwey transforms the word ''sinuses'' into ''Siracusa's''.<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/> She describes Kirchwey's breaking up of the word ''hemoglobin'' into ''he\u2013moglobin'' because the writer is talking about the birth of a baby boy, and Salter discusses the rhyming patterns. She notes how Kirchwey spent a year in Italy; many of the poems in this book are set there.<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/> She finds in his writing a quality of \"tenderness\", and sees a poet who \"can't shake his shockability\".<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/>\n\nSalter compared Kirchwey to poet [[Marianne Moore]] in terms of how the \"alliterative, assonant words hang heavy as lemons from their commas\" and in terms of stylistic approaches such as breaking words at the ends of lines and having a fairly \"loose treatment of meter.\"<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/> ''The Engrafted Word'' was listed as a \"notable book\" of 1998 by ''The New York Times''.<ref name=twsOctBjlk>{{cite news\n |title= Notable Books of 1998\n |publisher= The New York Times: Books\n |quote= Poems. By Karl Kirchwey. (Marian Wood/Holt, cloth, $23; Owl/Holt, paper, $13.) Typically steeped in myth, history and literature (without neglecting doses of sensuality), these poems propose that the transformative word of poetry can save souls. \n |date= December 6, 1998\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/12/06/reviews/notable-fiction.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n===Book reviewing by Kirchwey===\nKirchwey wrote reviews in ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', the ''[[New York Times Book Review]]'', and he has contributed literary essays to ''[[Parnassus: Poetry in Review]]'' and other journals.\n\nKirchwey reviewed a poetry book by [[Derek Walcott]]<ref name=twsOctB34er/> and described the Nobel Prize winner's latest collection of poems as \"intensely personal, revealing a deeper autobiographical intimacy.\"<ref name=twsOctBbnnn>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= Derek Walcott, Man of Many Voices\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= The Nobel Prize winner Derek Walcott's latest collection of poems is intensely personal, revealing a deeper autobiographical intimacy.\n |date= April 25, 2010\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/glogin?URI=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/books/review/Kirchwey-t.html&OQ=_rQ3D1Q26refQ3Dderek_walcott&OP=358ae36fQ2FDfozDKP8m,PP0Q3BDQ3BNQ2BNDN%28DQ3BQ3EDzPPQ3AmD,onQ5EofDUQ5E,8Q2FfopH0Q3FQ2F02Q26\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> Kirchwey reviewed poetry of Jeffrey Yang as well,<ref name=twsOctB8io/> writing that Yang \"speaks in tongues as if touched with a Pentecostal flame\" and \"leads the reader through a net of allusions in poems barnacled with hard words.\"<ref name=twsOctBxaas>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= Poetry's Shadow\n |publisher= The New York Times Sunday Book Review\n |quote= Jeffrey Yang speaks in tongues as if touched with a Pentecostal flame. He leads the reader through a net of allusions in poems barnacled with hard words.\n |date= December 19, 2008\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/21/books/review/Kirchwey-t.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref>\n\nKirchwey reviewed the novel ''The Dream Life of Sukhanov'' by [[Olga Grushin]] in 2006 for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''.<ref name=twsOctBhjkjj>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= 'Sukhanov' a brilliant novel about price of compromise\n |work= Chicago Tribune\n |quote= Olga Grushin's brilliant first novel, \"The Dream Life of Sukhanov\" (Putnam, 368 pages, $24.95), considers the case of 56-year-old Anatoly Pavlovich Sukhanov, whose past catches up with him during the last days of the Soviet Union.\n |date= August 3, 2006\n |url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-08-03/features/0608020307_1_anatoly-pavlovich-sukhanov-soviet-union-narrative\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> The novel is about an artist\u2013turned\u2013party official working for the [[communism|communist]] media as an art critic named Sukhanov whose \"past catches up with him during the last days of the [[Soviet Union]].\"<ref name=twsOctBhjkjj/> Kirchwey wrote:\n\n{{cquote|Seldom has a first novel so perfectly captured a historical moment that seems most real because it resonates with the disaster of an individual life. There is no escape for Sukhanov, and no going back: There is none for any of us. Time sees to that.<br/>--Karl Kirchwey in 2006 describing ''The Dream Life of Sukhanov'' <ref name=twsOctBhjkjj/>}}\n\n===Awards===\n* 1997 Paris Review Prize for Poetic Drama for ''Airdales & Cipher''\n* Norma Farber First Book Award from the Poetry Society of America), for ''A Wandering Island''\n* [[Ingram Merrill Foundation]] grant<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/><ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/>\n* 1994 John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/> grant<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/7891-karl-kirchwey |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 27, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604000430/http://www.gf.org/fellows/7891-karl-kirchwey |archive-date=June 4, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[National Endowment for the Arts]]<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/><ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/>\n* 1994\u201395 Rome Prize in Literature<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/><ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Expand list|date=September 2015}}\n\n===Poetry===\n\n====Collections====\n* {{cite book |author=Kirchwey, Karl |authorlink= |authormask= |title=A wandering island |location=Princeton, NJ |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=1990}}\n* {{cite book| title=Those I Guard | publisher=Harcourt Brace| year=1993| isbn=978-0-15-190170-8 }}<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n* {{cite book| title=The Engrafted Word | publisher=Henry Holt| year=1998| isbn=978-0-8050-5607-5 }}<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n* {{cite book| title=At the Palace of Jove | publisher=Marian Wood Books\u2013\u2013Putnam's| year=2002| isbn=978-0-399-14919-1 }}<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n* {{cite book| title=The Happiness of This World: Poetry and Prose | publisher=Marian Wood Books\u2013\u2013Putnam's| year=2007| isbn=978-0-399-15365-5 }}<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n* {{cite book| title=Mount Lebanon | publisher=Marian Wood Books\u2013\u2013Putnam's| year=2011| isbn=978-0-399-15727-1 }}<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n\n==== List of poems ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:90%;\"\n|-\n!width=25%|Title\n!|Year\n!|First published\n!|Reprinted/collected\n|-\n|Troia\n|2013\n|{{cite journal |authormask= |date=March 25, 2013 |title=Troia |department= |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |volume=89 |issue=6 |page=98 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/03/25/troia |accessdate=11 September 2015}}\n|\n|}\n\n*{{cite journal| url=http://www.newyorker.com/fiction/poetry/2008/06/30/080630po_poem_kirchwey| title=Propofol| work=The New Yorker| date=June 30, 2008 }}\n*{{cite journal| url=http://www.poetryfoundation.org/archive/poem.html?id=181177| title=Lemnos| work=Poetry|date=March 2008}}\n*{{cite journal| url=http://www.poetryfoundation.org/archive/poem.html?id=181178| title=The Red Portrait| work=Poetry|date=March 2008}}\n*[http://www.slate.com/id/2119067/ \"Fireflys\", ''Slate'', July 12, 2005]\n*[http://www.slate.com/id/10139/ \"The Tragic Sense of Life\", ''Slate'', December 9, 1998]\n*[http://www.newcriterion.com/articles.cfm/Three-oaks-2521 \"Three oaks\", ''The New Criterion'', November 2006]\n\n===Translation===\n* {{cite book| title=Poems Under Saturn | publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2011| isbn=978-0-691-14486-3 }}<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n\n===Verse Play===\n* ''Airdales & Cipher'', based on the Alcestis of [[Euripides]].<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n\n===Anthologies===\n* The KGB Bar Book of Poems (2000)<ref name=twsOctBg677/>\n* {{cite book | title=The Best of the Best American Poetry, 1987\u20131998 | publisher=Scribner | year=1998 | isbn=978-0-684-84279-0 | url=https://archive.org/details/bestofbestamer00scri }}\n* Twentieth Century Latin American Poetry: a Bilingual Anthology (1996)<ref name=twsOctBg677/>\n* Twentieth Century Poems on the Gospels: an Anthology (1996)<ref name=twsOctBg677/>\n* After Ovid: New Metamorphoses (1995)<ref name=twsOctBg677/>\n* {{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/?id=zeyHlt71nq0C&pg=PA323 | title=Bright pages: Yale writers 1701\u20132001| editor=J. D. McClatchy| publisher=Yale University Press| year=2001| isbn=978-0-300-08944-8 }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aarome.org/ American Academy in Rome website]\n* [http://www.brynmawr.edu/find/facultystaff/index.html Karl Kirchwey page at Bryn Mawr website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kirchwey, Karl}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Yale College alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Phillips Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:The New Yorker people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Karl Kirchwey\n| image = File:T.S. Eliot and the Mind of Europe - 25841267534 (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Kirchwey speaks at a Boston University event in 2016\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1956|02|25}}\n| birth_place = \n| nationality = American\n| occupation = Poet,<br/> translator,<br/> teacher,<br/> literary curator\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| residence = Boston, Massachusetts\n| alma_mater = [[Yale College|Yale]] [[bachelor of arts]] 1979<br/>[[master of arts]] from [[Columbia University|Columbia]]<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n| notable_works= ''The Engrafted Word''<br/>1998<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n| influenced  = \n| website = \n| signature = \n| parents =\n}}\n\n'''Karl Kirchwey''' (born February 25, 1956) is an award\u2013winning<ref name=twsOctBg677/> American poet who has lived in both Europe and the United States and whose work is strongly influenced by the [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] and [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] past. He often looks to the [[classical world]] for inspiration, with themes which have included loss, loneliness, nostalgia, and modern atrocities, and how the past relates to the present.<ref name=twsOctByree/><ref name=twsOctBxfsf/> While he is best known for his poems, he also is a [[book reviewer]],<ref name=twsOctB34er>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= Derek Walcott, Man of Many Voices \n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= More than almost any other contemporary poet, Derek Walcott might seem to be fulfilling T. S. Eliot's program for poetry. He has distinguished himself in all of what Eliot described as the \"three voices of poetry\": the lyric, the narrative or epic, and the dramatic. \n |date= April 22, 2010\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/books/review/Kirchwey-t.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctB8io>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= Poetry's Shadow\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= But whereas Lawrence is discursively tender, and Rexroth wry and epigrammatically clever, Jeffrey Yang speaks in tongues as if touched with a Pentecostal flame. He leads the reader through a net of allusions in poems barnacled with hard words. \n |date= December 19, 2008 \n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/21/books/review/Kirchwey-t.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> award-winning teacher of creative writing,<ref name=twsOctBvbcv>{{cite news\n |title= Creative Writing Program Director Karl Kirchwey to Serve as Andrew Heiskell Arts Director at the American Academy in Rome\n |publisher= Bryn Mawr\n |quote= In 2003 Kirchwey received Bryn Mawr's Rosalyn R. Schwartz Teaching Award.\n |date= April 27, 2010\n |url= http://news.brynmawr.edu/?p=5525\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> translator, arts administrator,<ref name=twsOctB75544/> [[curator|literary curator]], and advocate for writers and writing. He was director of the Unterberg Poetry Center of the [[92nd Street Y]] for 13 years,<ref name=twsOctB75544/> directed and taught in the Creative Writing Program at Bryn Mawr College from 2000 to 2010,<ref name=twsOctBeqqq/> served as [[Andrew Heiskell]] Arts Director at the [[American Academy in Rome]] from 2010 to 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aarome.org/#rt=news&rid=162|title=American Academy in Rome &#124; American Academy in Rome|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref> and is currently professor and director of the MFA Program in creative writing at [[Boston University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bu.edu/creativewriting/karl-kirchwey/|title=Karl Kirchwey \u00bb Writing \u00bb Boston University|website=www.bu.edu|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===College years===\n[[File:Phillips Academy, Andover, MA - Samuel Phillips Hall.JPG|thumb|right|Kirchwey attended Phillips Academy in Andover.]]\nKirchwey was born in 1956 and graduated from [[Phillips Academy]] in [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]] in 1974 in the boarding school's first co-educational class, which included jazz musician [[Bill Cunliffe]], software executive [[Peter Currie (businessman)|Peter Currie]], actor [[Dana Delany]], painter [[Julian Hatton]], writer [[Nate Lee]], political commentator [[Heather Mac Donald]], restaurateur [[Priscilla Martel]], TV producer [[Jonathan Meath]], editor [[Sara Nelson]], and sculptor [[Gar Waterman]]. He attended [[Yale College|Yale]], but described his first two undergraduate years as \"unfocused and unproductive.\"<ref name=twsOctBeqqq>{{cite news\n |author= John swansburg\n |title= At Yale, Lessons in Writing and in Life\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= Karl Kirchwey, who graduated from Yale in 1979, recently became the director of creative writing at Bryn Mawr College, after having run the Unterberg Poetry Center at the 92nd Street Y for over a decade. He remembers his first two years at Yale as unfocused and unproductive.\n |date= April 29, 2001\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/29/nyregion/at-yale-lessons-in-writing-and-in-life.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> He took a class on [[Metre (poetry)|versification]] taught by Penelope Laurans, which gave him the sense that he had an \"ear for verse\", but his work was \"less than diligent\" in his own estimation.<ref name=twsOctBeqqq/> He took a year off and worked at Cutler's Record Shop in [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]]. After his year off, he studied with poet [[John Hollander]] and discovered that building a life around the task of writing poetry was possible. Kirchwey described Hollander as a master of both [[British poetry|English]] and [[American poetry]] and said:\n\n{{cquote|Since he (John Hollander) is a poet himself ... he conveyed a passion for that knowledge as a source of current inspiration.<br/>--Karl Kirchwey in 2001<ref name=twsOctBeqqq/>}}\n\nHollander taught him that poems were more than mere creations, but have an inspirational force, and gave Kirchwey greater respect for intellectual and artistic pursuits, as well as for Yale.\n\n{{cquote|Why was Yale unique? At that point it wasn't because there was a creative writing program there, because there wasn't (and still isn't). Instead, it had to do with a sense that creative writing, that poetry in my case, was arising out of this superb intellectual climate where art was taken seriously.<br/>--Karl Kirchwey in 2001<ref name=twsOctBeqqq/>}}\n\nKirchwey graduated with a [[bachelor of arts]] degree in [[English literature]] from Yale and with an master of arts in [[English literature]] from [[Columbia University|Columbia]].<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n\n===Teaching===\nBetween 1979 and 1984, Kirchwey taught English literature and composition at the Andover Summer Session. He also taught at the [[The American School In Switzerland|American School in Switzerland]] in [[Lugano, Switzerland|Lugano]], and at Elisabeth Irwin High School in New York City.\n\n[[File:Aeneas Creusa Louvre OA7554.jpg|thumb|right|In Vergil's ''Aeneid'', the hero Aeneas sees a vision of his dead wife [[Creusa]], who tries to relieve Aeneas from grieving by telling him that her death had been fated.]]\nFrom 1995 to 1997, Kirchwey drove weekly between New York City and western Massachusetts, where he taught writing at [[Smith College]]. During these drives, he would listen to tapes of [[epic poetry]], including a translation of [[Vergil]] by [[Robert Fitzgerald]]. During one drive, Kirchwey felt lost in the entangled ramps of what his grandmother had once termed the \"Hartford spaghetti\" stretch of Interstate 91; he described it as \"bewildering, tortuous, and layered are the whorls of its entrance and exit ramps\".<ref name=twsOctBv122/> Kirchwey wrote later how that driving experience had reminded him of Vergil's hero Aeneas, who after having fled [[Troy]] during its nighttime destruction by the Greek army, returned to the burning city to search for his missing wife Creusa, but who became lost temporarily.<ref name=twsOctBv122/> Creusa's ghost appears to Aeneas to tell him that her death had been fated and that he can do nothing about it and that he must continue with his life.<ref name=twsOctBv122/> Kirchwey wrote how his experience in Hartford was similar to that of Aeneas in Troy:\n\n{{cquote|And I felt this huge weariness of the hero as he was told, with a [[wisdom]] surpassing human understanding, that he would build his life over again and found a new race in a new land ... This prophecy, the inexorability of the exchange of what one loves best for what [[Destiny|fate]] will have one do, seemed so authentically to mix bitterness and rapture, my own vision blurred for a while as the lights came on outside [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]] and I continued home. <br/>-- Karl Kirchwey, writing in ''Poets and critics read Vergil'' edited by Sarah Spence.<ref name=twsOctBv122>{{cite news\n |author= Sarah Spence (editor)\n |title= Poets and Critics Read Vergil\n |publisher= Yale University\n |quote= see pages 184\u2013185\n |year= 2001\n |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=tyZtZ95UHvsC&pg=PA184 \n |isbn=0-300-08376-9\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref>}}\n\nKirchwey taught at Smith College, Yale, [[Wesleyan University|Wesleyan]], and in the master of fine arts program at Columbia.<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/> He taught at Bryn Mawr from 2000 to 2014, where he was professor of the arts and director of creative writing.<ref name=twsOctBeqqq/> From 2010 to 2013, he took leave from Bryn Mawr to serve as [[Andrew Heiskell]] Arts Director at the [[American Academy in Rome]].<ref name=twsOctBcsdde>{{cite web\n |title= Karl Kirchwey\n |publisher= Boston University\n |quote= Karl Kirchwey is the author of six books of poems: A Wandering Island (Princeton University Press, 1990; recipient of the Norma Farber First Book Award from the Poetry Society of America), Those I Guard (Harcourt Brace and Company, 1993), The Engrafted Word (Henry Holt, 1998; a New York Times \u201cNotable Book of the Year\u201d), and At the Palace of Jove (2002), The Happiness of This World: Poetry and Prose (2007) and Mount Lebanon (2011), all published by Marian Wood Books/Putnam\u2019s.\n |date= June 15, 2014\n |url= http://www.bu.edu/creativewriting/karl-kirchwey/\n |accessdate= 28 July 2014\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctBzxcxx>{{cite news\n |author= Karen Heller\n |title= Bryn Mawr shows creative side as it makes way for arts\n |work= Chicago Tribune\n |quote= And that's fine by Karl Kirchwey. \"My job is to put Bryn Mawr on the map for literature, and as a place to study creative writing,\" says the long, lanky, passionate poet in command of an astonishing Rolodex. The author of four books of poetry, many inspired by classical literature, and a graduate of Yale and Columbia, Kirchwey has been awarded Guggenheim, National Endowment for the Arts and Ingram Merrill fellowships, as well as the vaunted Rome Prize in Literature. In the three years since the 47-year-old poet left the famed Unterberg Poetry Center at New York's 92nd Street Y, Kirchwey has quietly, but quickly, increased attention to the written word on the sylvan, suburban campus.\n |date= May 1, 2003\n |url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-05-01/features/0305010107_1_bryn-mawr-college-marianne-moore-samson-agonistes\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> At Bryn Mawr he taught creative writing courses in poetry and memoir and literature courses in [[classical mythology|Classical Myth]] and its contemporary updates, [[modernist poetry]], and [[American poetry#Modernism and after|contemporary American poetry]].<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/> He received Bryn Mawr's Rosalyn R. Schwartz Teaching Award in 2003.<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/>\n\n[[File:Entrance Bryn Mawr.JPG|thumb|right|Bryn Mawr College is located in a suburb near Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.]]\nAccording to one account, Bryn Mawr in the 1990s began a project to raise the national stature of its writing program, as well as \"its profile in the arts\" according to provost Ralph Kuncl, and Kirchwey was hired in 2000 as part of this effort.<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/> College president [[Nancy J. Vickers|Nancy Vickers]] applauded Kirchwey's efforts to bring talented writers to lecture on the campus.<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/> Kirchwey said:\n\n{{cquote|My job is to put Bryn Mawr on the map for literature, and as a place to study creative writing.<br/> \u2013 Karl Kirchwey in 2003.<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/>}}\n\nKirchwey helped bring numerous writers to campus including [[Nobel laureate]]s [[Derek Walcott]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> [[Nadine Gordimer]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> and [[Nigeria]]'s [[Wole Soyinka]], as well as writers such as [[Peter Cameron (writer)|Peter Cameron]], [[Sandra Cisneros]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> novelist [[E. L. Doctorow]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> [[Umberto Eco]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> [[Jessica Hagedorn]], [[Maxine Hong Kingston]], [[James Lasdun]],<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/> [[Peter Matthiessen]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> novelist [[Ian McEwan]], [[Sigrid Nunez]], [[Susan-Lori Parks]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> [[Robert Pinsky]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> [[Zadie Smith]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> [[Mark Strand]],<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> playwright [[August Wilson]], and others. Actors [[Claire Bloom]] and [[John Neville (actor)|John Neville]] did a stage reading of [[John Milton|Milton's]] ''[[Samson Agonistes]]''.<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/> A Bryn Mawr publication described Kirchwey's efforts as successful, and wrote that he diversified and expanded the creative writing program to make it a \"premier stop\" for writers in the Philadelphia region.<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/>\n\nIn 2010, Kirchwey was named the Andrew Heiskell Arts Director at the American Academy in Rome, which is an independent privately funded institution that encourages scholarly and artistic projects associated with the culture of Rome.<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> Its mission is \"to foster the pursuit of advanced research and independent study in the fine arts and humanities,\" according to a statement on its website.<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx11>{{cite web\n |title= Mission statement\n |publisher= American Academy in Rome\n |quote= The mission of the American Academy in Rome, founded in 1894, is to foster the pursuit of advanced research and independent study in the fine arts and humanities.\n |date= October 18, 2010\n |url= http://www.aarome.org/\n |accessdate= 18 October 2010\n}}</ref> Kirchwey returned to Bryn Mawr for the 2013\u201314 academic year.<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> A Bryn Mawr publication described Kirchwey's role in Italy as \"shaping and articulating the Academy's broad vision for the arts\" in terms of guiding programs.<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> Beginning in September 2014 he will be Professor and Director of the MFA Program in Creative Writing at [[Boston University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.bu.edu/crwr/2014/07/11/welcome-karl-kirchwey-literary-links/|title=Welcome, Karl Kirchwey! + literary links &#124; BU Creative Writing|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nKirchwey has written poetry consistently during his career, and by 2011 had published six books of poetry in addition to a translation of Paul Verlaine's first book of poems as ''Poems Under Saturn''. He was influenced by the civilizations of classical Ancient Rome and Ancient Greece and has a European orientation in some of his poems, as well as a [[religion|religious sensibility]].<ref name=twsOctBbdss/> For example, his poem entitled \"Mutabor\" meaning ''change'' had references to the [[Hindu]] god [[Parvati]] and [[Shiva]] and a section of the poem, which appeared in the online publication ''[[Poetry (magazine)|Poetry Daily]]'', described a boy and a girl in a gorge.<ref name=twsOctBbdss>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= Mutabor: The Gorge\n |work= Poetry Daily\n |quote= They went down to the gorge of the Petite Gryonne ... in May, this was, a boy and a girl ... a hollow melted in it like the cave where immortal Parvati ... rubbed her own skin to make the jovial god... (from Mutabor: The Gorge by Karl Kirchwey)\n |date= November 2009\n |url= http://poems.com/poem.php?date=14566\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> Kirchwey based the poem on his memory as a youth of a cold stream called the Petite Gyronne near a bridge that ran in a secret gorge between the village of Chesi\u00e8res and the ski resort of Villars in the [[Alps Mountains]] in the French-speaking part of [[Switzerland]].<ref name=twsOctBbdss/> He wrote that a place near the gorge was where it had been said that \"the bravest of the boys would walk the entire length of the narrow bridge-railing, a hundred feet or more above the stream bed, even (once) blindfolded.\"<ref name=twsOctBbdss/> In Kirchwey's poem, the boy and the girl are lovers in a hollow near a heap of melting snow in May who \"faced with the water's endlessness\" and the \"untranslatable grief of the bird's paraphrase\" became wise in their lovemaking: \"they were never wiser than in that knowledge,\" he wrote in the poem.<ref name=twsOctBbdss/> In addition, events in his life, such as the death of his mother, have influenced his poetry.<ref name=twsOctB2111>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= The Red Portrait\n |publisher= Poetry Foundation\n |quote= Last night she came to me, my mother, dead: but as she was in the photo, that last Christmas ... ...  I told her how her life had informed mine, and I begged her to come to me again ... ... But she smiled at me and began to fade. \u2013 Karl Kirchwey\n |date= March 2008\n |url= http://www.poetryfoundation.org/archive/poem.html?id=181178\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref>\n\nKirchwey spent from September 1994 to July 1995 at the Academy in Rome as part of the Rome Prize, and described the experience as having \"completely shaped\" his third book of poems.<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/>\n\nIn 1998, Kirchwey's ''The Engrafted Word'' was published by Holt in hardcover and paperback versions.<ref name=twsOctB5999>{{cite news\n |author= Libby Larsen\n |title= Customer reviews\n |publisher= Amazon.com\n |quote= Kirchwey does an amazing job of synthesizing ideas from a number of spheres- such as obstetrics, physics, superstition, mythology, biology, religion, chemistry, Roman history and poetry. Kirchwey accomplishes said task by engrafting technical words upon each other, words that outwardly have little in common. Moreover, Kirchwey's great use of setting enables me to feel the location of each poem. \n |date= April 10, 2000\n |url= https://www.amazon.com/Engrafted-Word-Poems-Karl-Kirchwey/product-reviews/0805056076/ref=dp_top_cm_cr_acr_txt?ie=UTF8&showViewpoints=1\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> It revealed Kirchwey's wide inquiry into disparate areas including [[obstetrics]], [[physics]], [[superstition]], [[mythology]], [[biology]], religion, [[chemistry]], and [[Roman history]].<ref name=twsOctB5999/> He ''engrafted'' technical words upon each other, sometimes words which seemed initially to have little in common with each other, and magically ''engrafts'' the \"past with the present\", according to one reviewer.<ref name=twsOctB5999/>\n\nIn 2002, ''At the Palace of Jove: Poems'' was published by Marian Wood Books/Putnam's. The book had classical references and was described by ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' as an exploration of how the past impacts the present.<ref name=twsOctByree>\n{{cite news\n |title= Nature & Environment\n |work= Publishers Weekly\n |quote= At the Palace of Jove (Oct., $26; paper $15) by Karl Kirchwey. Verse explores the impact of the past on the present.\n |date= August 12, 2002\n |url= http://reg.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/20020812/31096-fall-2002-hardcovers-nature-amp-environment-to-reference-.html?refresh\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110715131538/http://reg.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/20020812/31096-fall-2002-hardcovers-nature-amp-environment-to-reference-.html?refresh\n |archive-date= July 15, 2011\n |url-status= dead\n |df= mdy-all\n }}\n</ref> The magazine felt that Kirchwey's poems entitled ''Elegies'' weren't strictly about [[mourning]] but rather were \"quiet inquiries into what the mind does to compensate for spiritual silence.\"<ref name=twsOctByree/>\n\nIn 2007, Kirchwey published ''The Happiness of this World'', which included poems such as \"Reading Akhmatova\" in which a child's [[speech therapy]] is contrasted with a Russian poet's experience and in which Kirchwey wrote phrases such as the \"widening diction of experience\".<ref name=twsOctB>{{cite news\n |author= Carl Rosin\n |title= Customer Reviews\n |publisher= Amazon.com\n |quote= I am especially fond of \"Reading Akhmatova\", in which a child's speech therapy runs through a book of the Russian poet's far-from-childish words and themes. We adults hear things in Akhmatova \u2013 this poem has a literariness that seems typical of Kirchwey's work \u2013 that clangs against the child's innocent enunciation of the words. The \"widening diction of experience\" evoked here is one of those rare lines (in modern poetry) with staying power for me \u2013 it has resonated with me for weeks.\n |date= February 23, 2008\n |url= https://www.amazon.com/Happiness-this-World-Karl-Kirchwey/product-reviews/0399153659/ref=dp_top_cm_cr_acr_txt?ie=UTF8&showViewpoints=1\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> The book included a prose memoir entitled \"A Yatra for Yama\", which described a journey Kirchwey made through Asia related to a family story in which a namesake uncle died in a [[World War II]] plane crash during the battle for [[Saipan]].<ref name=twsOctB/> A ''yatra'' is a journey.<ref name=twsOctB/>\n\nKirchwey's poems have appeared in ''[[AGNI (magazine)|AGNI]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bu.edu/agni/authors/K/Karl-Kirchwey.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 27, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226215301/http://www.bu.edu/agni/authors/K/Karl-Kirchwey.html |archive-date=December 26, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[The Atlantic]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[Grand Street (magazine)|Grand Street]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The Hudson Review]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The Kenyon Review]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The Nation]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thenation.com/doc/20041115/kirchwey |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 27, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007062346/http://www.thenation.com/doc/20041115/kirchwey |archive-date=October 7, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[The New Criterion]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The New Republic]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[Salmagundi]]'', ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nybooks.com/authors/130|title=Karl Kirchwey|website=The New York Review of Books|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/bios/karl_kirchwey/search?contributorName=karl%20kirchwey |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 27, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607062638/http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/bios/karl_kirchwey/search?contributorName=karl%20kirchwey |archive-date=June 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Parnassus (magazine)|Parnassus]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[Partisan Review]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[Poetry (magazine)|Poetry]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The Southwest Review]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The American Scholar (magazine)|American Scholar]]'', [[Sewanee Review]]'', ''[[Arion (journal)|Arion]]'', ''[[Tin House]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> ''[[The Yale Review]]'',<ref name=twsOctBg677/> and elsewhere.\n\nWhile known best for his poetry, Kirchwey also wrote the play ''Airdales & Cipher'', which was presented as a public reading at several venues, including the Appalachian Summer Festival in [[Boone, North Carolina]], as well as the 92nd Street Y.<ref name=twsOctBg677>\n{{cite news\n |title= Karl Kirchwey: Associate Professor and Director of Creative Writing\n |publisher= Bryn Mawr\n |quote= His play in verse entitled Airedales & Cipher, based on the Alcestis of Euripides, received the 1997 Paris Review Prize for Poetic Drama\n |year= 2010\n |url= http://www.brynmawr.edu/english/Faculty_and_Staff/smKirchwey.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20101008161358/http://www.brynmawr.edu/english/Faculty_and_Staff/smKirchwey.html\n |archive-date= October 8, 2010\n |url-status= dead\n |df= mdy-all\n }}\n</ref> The play was based on a work by Greek playwright [[Euripides]] entitled ''Alcestis'' and won the ''[[The Paris Review|Paris Review Prize]]'' in 1997 in the category of poetic drama.<ref name=twsOctBg677/> He has also read aloud the works of other writers such as [[Eudora Welty]].<ref name=twsOctB4ee3>\n{{cite news\n |author= Bob Summer\n |title= Volume 245 Issue\n |work= Publishers Weekly\n |quote= Notable, too, was the unusually large audience drawn to New York City's 92nd St. Y for the Library's launch event, an evening of readings of the honoree's stories by Ann Beattie, Ford, Randall Kenan, Karl Kirchwey (substituting for William Maxwell),\n |date= April 12, 1999\n |url= http://reg.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/19990412/40153-adoring-eudora-.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110715131627/http://reg.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/19990412/40153-adoring-eudora-.html\n |archive-date= July 15, 2011\n |url-status= dead\n |df= mdy-all\n }}\n</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Kirchwey published a sixth volume of poems entitled ''Mount Lebanon'', his third book with [[G. P. Putnam's Sons|Marian Wood Books\u2013Putnam's]].<ref name=twsOctBvbcv/> ''[[Publishers Weekly]] wrote, \"Kirchwey seamlessly melds the contemporary and commonplace with the past and mythical,\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Karl Kirchwey. Putnam, $30 (112p) ISBN 978-0-399-15727-1 |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-399-15727-1 |title=Fiction Book Review: Mount Lebanon by Karl Kirchwey. Putnam, $30 (112p) ISBN 978-0-399-15727-1 |publisher=Publishersweekly.com |date=2011-03-21 |accessdate=2020-01-30}}</ref> and in ''[[Booklist]]'', Ray Olson remarked, \"Highly literate, Kirchwey uses his knowledge of religion, art, and history to inform his experience of the world....Expertly crafted throughout, this book attests a consummately cultured, thoroughly contemporary poet.\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vufind.uhls.org/vufind/Record/860312/Reviews |title=Archived copy |access-date=July 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140805081323/http://vufind.uhls.org/vufind/Record/860312/Reviews |archive-date=August 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Also in 2011, [[Princeton University Press]] published Kirchwey's translation of French poet [[Paul Verlaine]]'s first book as ''Poems Under Saturn''. Kirchwey's seventh book of poems, revisiting some of the sites of his third book ''The Engrafted Word'' and entitled ''Stumbling Blocks: Roman Poems'' is forthcoming.\n\n[[File:92Y jeh.jpg|thumb|right|The 92nd Street Y in New York City]]\n\n===92nd Street Y===\nIn 1984, Kirchwey joined the Poetry Center as assistant to the director of the Unterberg Poetry Center of the [[92nd Street Y]] in New York City, and became director in 1987, and he held this post until 2000.<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/><ref name=twsOctBeqqq/><ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/><ref name=twsOctBe2q3>{{cite news\n |title= Director Named at 92nd Street Y\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= Frederick Noonan, director of the Y's musical programs, and Karl Kirchwey, director of the poetry center, are to continue to direct their departments.\n |date= March 25, 2000\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/25/arts/director-named-at-92nd-street-y.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctB6yu>{{cite news\n |author= Glenn collins\n |title= When the Writers Read, the Readers Listen\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= ''There is a certain volatility about putting an audience together with a writer,'' said Karl Kirchwey, director of the Poetry Center of the 92d Street Y. ''Some authors look out at an audience and spontaneously decide not to read what they were going to. I really believe that in going to readings, people are reacting against the pre-packaged video and radio that is their normal fare and choosing a kind of live and unrehearsed spontaneity.'' (page 2)\n |date= October 23, 1989\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1989/10/23/books/when-the-writers-read-the-readers-listen.html?pagewanted=2\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> He [[curator|curated]] the Poetry Center's annual reading series, which included writers in all genres such as poetry, fiction, nonfiction, and drama.<ref name=twsOctB75544/> He staffed and taught a creative writing program for nonmatriculating adults. He also curated a series of lectures by literary biographers called \" Biographers and Brunch\" .<ref name=twsOctB75544/> He instituted programs that explored connections between literature and other art forms such as music and [[visual arts]].<ref name=twsOctB75544/> He was described as focusing on [[verse drama]] and presented plays by Nobel laureates [[Seamus Heaney]] and [[Derek Walcott]], as well as ones by [[Rita Dove]].<ref name=twsOctB75544/> In addition,  programs for high school students from New York City were presented.<ref name=twsOctB75544/> The center won grants from the Lila Wallace\u2013Reader's Digest Fund which helped make possible a national stage tour of Robert Pinsky's translation of Dante's ''[[Dante's Inferno|Inferno]]''.<ref name=twsOctB75544/> There was a thirteen-part radio series entitled ''The Poet's Voice'' broadcast on WNYC radio and later on ''[[National Public Radio]]''.<ref name=twsOctB75544/> The annual budget for the poetry center grew by a quarter of a million dollars, according to an account from the 92nd Street Y.<ref name=twsOctB75544/>\n\nAs director, Kirchwey encouraged New Yorkers to experience live readings by authors, since the format permits a \"certain volatility\" and spontaneity, in his view; readers benefit from hearing the author speak aloud, in person, and do not hear the usual \"prepackaged video and radio.\"<ref name=twsOctB6yu/> Kirchwey said that in some situations, authors who had been prepared to read a certain passage had changed their minds at the last instant upon seeing an audience, and read something else; in this sense, the medium is more dynamic than broadcast media such as television or radio.<ref name=twsOctB6yu/> Kirchwey commented in 1998 that he thought that more people were attending live readings, and that audiences were getting younger on average.<ref name=twsOctB6yu/> Kirchwey introduced writers such as [[Alice Walker]].<ref name=twsOctBjlop>{{cite news\n |title= Introduction by Karl Kirchwey \n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= On Tuesday, October 13, The New York Times and the 92nd Street Y presented a live broadcast of Alice Walker reading from her new novel, \"By the Light of My Father's Smile\". \n |year= 1998\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/10/04/specials/walker.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> Kirchwey has read his own poems on occasion.<ref name=twsOctBpyrt>{{cite news\n |title= Arts Briefing\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= The event tonight is a concert reading of Milton's verse play ''Samson Agonistes,'' directed by Robert Scanlan and starring Claire Bloom, John Neville, Jack Willis and Alvin Epstein, as well as the poets John Hollander, Karl Kirchwey and Rosanna Warren. (p.3)\n |date= April 21, 2003\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2003/04/21/movies/arts-briefing.html?pagewanted=3\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctBr654>{{cite news\n |title= SPARE TIMES: Feb. 9 \u2013 Feb. 15\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= Monday at 8:15&nbsp;pm, Karl Kirchwey, Grace Schulman and David Yezzi will read from their poems and prose;\n |date= February 9, 2007\n |url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E04E7D9113FF93AA35751C0A9619C8B63\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> Kirchwey attended events such as one honoring poet [[Stanley Kunitz]].<ref name=twsOctB0o9o>{{cite news\n |author= Gary shapiro \n |title= 'Leaves of Grass' at 150, Kunitz at (Almost) 100\n |publisher= The New York Sun\n |quote= STANLEY'S CENTENNIAL Poet Stanley Kunitz's 100th birthday is on July 29. But friends, family, and admirers filled the Tribeca Performing Arts Center to celebrate early. Last month Karl Kirchwey, Marie Howe, Lucie Brock-Broido, Gerald Stern, and others paid tribute to Mr. Kunitz before an audience filled with poets,\n |date= June 2, 2005\n |url= http://www.nysun.com/arts/leaves-of-grass-at-150-kunitz-at-almost-100/14801/\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> Kirchwey formally left the post of director of the 92nd Street Y in June 2000.<ref name=twsOctB75544>{{cite news\n |author=Alix Friedman \n |title=POETRY CENTER DIRECTOR KARL KIRCHWEY LEAVES 92nd STREET Y \n |publisher=92nd Street Y \n |quote=The 92nd Street Y announces the departure of Karl Kirchwey, longtime director of the 92nd Street Y Unterberg Poetry Center. Mr. Kirchwey will become Director of Creative Writing and Senior Lecturer in the Arts at Bryn Mawr College starting next fall. The Poetry Center is a program of the 92nd Street Y Tisch Center for the Arts, the Y's arts presenting division. \n |date=June 13, 2000 \n |url=http://www.92y.org/content/karl_kirchwey_leaves_poetry_center.asp\n |accessdate=15 October 2010 \n}}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Upon his departure in 2000, executive director Sol Adler said:\n\n{{cquote|It is with deep gratitude tinged with wistfulness that I accept Karl's resignation. He has done a great deal to honor and reflect upon the rich tradition of the Poetry Center, just as he has continued to attract new individual talents to our stage. We will miss him and wish him the very best. \u2013 Sol Adler in 2000.<ref name=twsOctB75544/>}}\n\n===Reviews of Kirchwey's poetry===\nA review of ''The Engrafted Word'' by writer [[Mary Jo Salter]] in ''[[The New York Times]]'' suggested Kirchwey's book of poems was ''transformative'' and ''elegant''.<ref name=twsOctBxfsf>{{cite news\n |author= Mary jo salter\n |title= Transfigurations: Karl Kirchwey believes that the poetic word can save our souls. \n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= Those readers familiar with Kirchwey's earlier work know him as a poet for whom the world of antiquity is as real as this morning's breakfast. The aural transformation from ''sinuses'' to ''Siracusa's'' comes from deep within the maker's sensibility. \n |date= August 9, 1998\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/08/09/reviews/980809.09saltert.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> Salter applauded Kirchwey's \"sensual accuracies\" in such poems by commenting on one of Kirchwey's poetic lines. Salter writes: \"A [[Medical ultrasonography|sonogram]]\u2014that routine magic whereby a mother's womb turns into a crystal ball\u2014opens Karl Kirchwey's elegant third collection of poems.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/08/09/reviews/980809.09saltert.html| work=The New York Times| date=August 9, 1998| title=Transfigurations \u2013 Karl Kirchwey |author=Mary Jo Salter}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|Something of desk work and pornography\nthrough succulences of conducting gel.<br/>--Karl Kirchwey in ''The Engrafted Word''<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/>}}\n\nSalter suggested that the repeated syllables with the ''uck'' sound evoked the sound of the experience of a sonogram, including the discomfort.<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/> She described Kirchwey's poetry as being \"steeped in allusions to [[classical mythology]], history, literature.<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/> For example, she notes how Kirchwey transforms the word ''sinuses'' into ''Siracusa's''.<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/> She describes Kirchwey's breaking up of the word ''hemoglobin'' into ''he\u2013moglobin'' because the writer is talking about the birth of a baby boy, and Salter discusses the rhyming patterns. She notes how Kirchwey spent a year in Italy; many of the poems in this book are set there.<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/> She finds in his writing a quality of \"tenderness\", and sees a poet who \"can't shake his shockability\".<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/>\n\nSalter compared Kirchwey to poet [[Marianne Moore]] in terms of how the \"alliterative, assonant words hang heavy as lemons from their commas\" and in terms of stylistic approaches such as breaking words at the ends of lines and having a fairly \"loose treatment of meter.\"<ref name=twsOctBxfsf/> ''The Engrafted Word'' was listed as a \"notable book\" of 1998 by ''The New York Times''.<ref name=twsOctBjlk>{{cite news\n |title= Notable Books of 1998\n |publisher= The New York Times: Books\n |quote= Poems. By Karl Kirchwey. (Marian Wood/Holt, cloth, $23; Owl/Holt, paper, $13.) Typically steeped in myth, history and literature (without neglecting doses of sensuality), these poems propose that the transformative word of poetry can save souls. \n |date= December 6, 1998\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/12/06/reviews/notable-fiction.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n===Book reviewing by Kirchwey===\nKirchwey wrote reviews in ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', the ''[[New York Times Book Review]]'', and he has contributed literary essays to ''[[Parnassus: Poetry in Review]]'' and other journals.\n\nKirchwey reviewed a poetry book by [[Derek Walcott]]<ref name=twsOctB34er/> and described the Nobel Prize winner's latest collection of poems as \"intensely personal, revealing a deeper autobiographical intimacy.\"<ref name=twsOctBbnnn>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= Derek Walcott, Man of Many Voices\n |work= The New York Times\n |quote= The Nobel Prize winner Derek Walcott's latest collection of poems is intensely personal, revealing a deeper autobiographical intimacy.\n |date= April 25, 2010\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/glogin?URI=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/books/review/Kirchwey-t.html&OQ=_rQ3D1Q26refQ3Dderek_walcott&OP=358ae36fQ2FDfozDKP8m,PP0Q3BDQ3BNQ2BNDN%28DQ3BQ3EDzPPQ3AmD,onQ5EofDUQ5E,8Q2FfopH0Q3FQ2F02Q26\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> Kirchwey reviewed poetry of Jeffrey Yang as well,<ref name=twsOctB8io/> writing that Yang \"speaks in tongues as if touched with a Pentecostal flame\" and \"leads the reader through a net of allusions in poems barnacled with hard words.\"<ref name=twsOctBxaas>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= Poetry's Shadow\n |publisher= The New York Times Sunday Book Review\n |quote= Jeffrey Yang speaks in tongues as if touched with a Pentecostal flame. He leads the reader through a net of allusions in poems barnacled with hard words.\n |date= December 19, 2008\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/21/books/review/Kirchwey-t.html\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref>\n\nKirchwey reviewed the novel ''The Dream Life of Sukhanov'' by [[Olga Grushin]] in 2006 for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''.<ref name=twsOctBhjkjj>{{cite news\n |author= Karl Kirchwey\n |title= 'Sukhanov' a brilliant novel about price of compromise\n |work= Chicago Tribune\n |quote= Olga Grushin's brilliant first novel, \"The Dream Life of Sukhanov\" (Putnam, 368 pages, $24.95), considers the case of 56-year-old Anatoly Pavlovich Sukhanov, whose past catches up with him during the last days of the Soviet Union.\n |date= August 3, 2006\n |url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-08-03/features/0608020307_1_anatoly-pavlovich-sukhanov-soviet-union-narrative\n |accessdate= 15 October 2010\n}}</ref> The novel is about an artist\u2013turned\u2013party official working for the [[communism|communist]] media as an art critic named Sukhanov whose \"past catches up with him during the last days of the [[Soviet Union]].\"<ref name=twsOctBhjkjj/> Kirchwey wrote:\n\n{{cquote|Seldom has a first novel so perfectly captured a historical moment that seems most real because it resonates with the disaster of an individual life. There is no escape for Sukhanov, and no going back: There is none for any of us. Time sees to that.<br/>--Karl Kirchwey in 2006 describing ''The Dream Life of Sukhanov'' <ref name=twsOctBhjkjj/>}}\n\n===Awards===\n* 1997 Paris Review Prize for Poetic Drama for ''Airdales & Cipher''\n* Norma Farber First Book Award from the Poetry Society of America), for ''A Wandering Island''\n* [[Ingram Merrill Foundation]] grant<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/><ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/>\n* 1994 John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation<ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/> grant<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/7891-karl-kirchwey |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 27, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604000430/http://www.gf.org/fellows/7891-karl-kirchwey |archive-date=June 4, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[National Endowment for the Arts]]<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/><ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/>\n* 1994\u201395 Rome Prize in Literature<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/><ref name=twsOctBzxcxx/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Expand list|date=September 2015}}\n\n===Poetry===\n\n====Collections====\n* {{cite book |author=Kirchwey, Karl |authorlink= |authormask= |title=A wandering island |location=Princeton, NJ |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=1990}}\n* {{cite book| title=Those I Guard | publisher=Harcourt Brace| year=1993| isbn=978-0-15-190170-8 }}<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n* {{cite book| title=The Engrafted Word | publisher=Henry Holt| year=1998| isbn=978-0-8050-5607-5 }}<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n* {{cite book| title=At the Palace of Jove | publisher=Marian Wood Books\u2013\u2013Putnam's| year=2002| isbn=978-0-399-14919-1 }}<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n* {{cite book| title=The Happiness of This World: Poetry and Prose | publisher=Marian Wood Books\u2013\u2013Putnam's| year=2007| isbn=978-0-399-15365-5 }}<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n* {{cite book| title=Mount Lebanon | publisher=Marian Wood Books\u2013\u2013Putnam's| year=2011| isbn=978-0-399-15727-1 }}<ref name=twsOctBcsdde/>\n\n==== List of poems ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:90%;\"\n|-\n!width=25%|Title\n!|Year\n!|First published\n!|Reprinted/collected\n|-\n|Troia\n|2013\n|{{cite journal |authormask= |date=March 25, 2013 |title=Troia |department= |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |volume=89 |issue=6 |page=98 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/03/25/troia |accessdate=11 September 2015}}\n|\n|}\n\n*{{cite journal| url=http://www.newyorker.com/fiction/poetry/2008/06/30/080630po_poem_kirchwey| title=Propofol| work=The New Yorker| date=June 30, 2008 }}\n*{{cite journal| url=http://www.poetryfounda